hington]]\n\n==Cases==\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe first case of an infected Columbus resident was reported on March 14. The resident tested positive after returning from a cruise.<ref name=\"Ferenchik\">{{cite web|author=Mark Ferenchik |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200314/columbus-man-among-26-ohioans-diagnosed-with-coronavirus |title=Columbus man among 26 Ohioans diagnosed with coronavirus |work=The Columbus Dispatch |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 5, 2020, there are currently 4,043 cases and 119 total deaths in the entire state of Ohio, however in Columbia, Ohio there 416 cases confirmed in Columbus and Worthington<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbus.gov/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Outbreak 2019|website=www.columbus.gov|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n{{Main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{Main|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Engine House No. 16 (Columbus, Ohio).jpg|thumb|Empty downtown street, March 22]]\n[[File:Easton Town Center closed.jpg|thumb|[[Easton Town Center]], a major mall complex, in March]]\nDue to the COVID-19 outbreak schools were closed on March 17 and will remain close until May 1. All of Ohio's state playgrounds, cabins, marinas, golf courses and campgrounds have been closed. \n\nGovernor [[Mike DeWine]] issued a stay at home order for all Ohio's citizens until May 1 with the exception of citizens who provides essential services and has closed all non-essential indoors business like arcades and laser tag. \n\nThe COVID-19 outbreak has caused record-breaking levels of unemployment which has caused 187,784 citizens to file for unemployment and by the end of the week ending in March 27 was followed by 272,117.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Business closures and event cancellations===\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Film industry and the performing arts====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Food service and restaurant industry====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe city's restaurant industry was impacted by the state's bar and restaurant ban.\n\n====Hospitality industry====\nThe [[hospitality industry]] also experienced a wave of guest cancellations followed by a decline in bookings.\n\n====Impact on professional sports====\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}Main article: [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]<!--[[Arnold Classic]]-->\n\n==Impact on education==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}Due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], Ohio State University and other colleges and universities in the city cancelled in-person classes, moving to remote learning for the remainder of the semester. Additionally, with Governor [[Mike DeWine]] ordering all K-12 schools across the state to close through May 1, Columbus City Schools moved to remote learning during the closure. Columbus City Schools, along with other area school districts, began meal programs to provide to students under the age of 18. <ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\n==Impact on public transportation==\n[[File:Columbus, OH - COTA bus.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|[[Central Ohio Transit Authority|COTA]] buses notify riders to board using rear doors only]]\nIn early March, as the pandemic began affecting Ohio, the city's public transit ridership began dropping, approximately 40 percent. Its public transit agency [[Central Ohio Transit Authority|COTA]] began by introducing thorough cleaning measures, followed by reducing several rush hour services on March 17. On March 19, it suspended fare collection, making all rides temporarily free, and required passengers to board and depart buses from the rear doors. On the same day, it also modified all rush hour lines, and suspended its AirConnect and Night Owl services. On March 20, the agency recommended only using its services for essential travel; two days later it shut down several rush hour services and reduced frequencies of nine crosstown lines. On March 24, it stopped all rush hour services until further notice.<ref name=\"COVID\">{{Cite web |title=Major Service Change Announcements|work=Central Ohio Transit Authority|accessdate=March 19, 2020|url=https://www.cota.com/major-service-change-announcements/}}</ref> On March 26, the agency began \"dynamic service\" to pick up customers left at bus stops by too-full buses; the agency's current policy is for a maximum of 20 passengers per bus.<ref name=\"transit\">{{cite web|title=For Essential Travel, COTA and CoGo Are Still Available (But Scooters Aren't)|work=Columbus Underground|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.columbusunderground.com/for-essential-workers-cota-and-cogo-are-still-available-but-scooters-arent-bw1}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on religion==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Closures ==\n[[File:COSI sign.jpg|thumb|[[COSI (museum)|COSI]]'s entrance way sign, March 2020|271x271px]]\n\n\nOn March 13, [[Columbus Recreation and Parks]] closed all locations through April 3, followed by [[Columbus Metropolitan Library]] and [[Columbus Zoo and Aquarium]] closing all of their locations Through April 6.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\n[[Columbus Museum of Art]], [[Franklin Park Conservatory]], [[COSI]] (Center of Science and Industry), and [[National Veterans Memorial and Museum]] also shut there doors with  [[COSI]] closing through April 3 and the [[National Veterans Memorial and Museum]] closing through April 8.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\nOn March 16, All gyms, fitness centers, movie theaters, bowling alleys, public recreation centers, indoor water parks and trampoline parks followed by Hollywood Casino are closed.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\nOn March 18, BMV closes a majority of its locations (180 locations) but still operating 5 of its locations. Salons, Spas, Barbershops, Nail Salons, and Tattoo Parlors are closed as well.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\nOn March 20, Columbus Idea Foundry lays of all of its workers with the inclusion of Columbus Idea Foundry CEO Casey McCarty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themetropreneur.com/columbus/columbus-idea-foundry-lays-off-staff/|title=Columbus Idea Foundry Lays Off Staff - The Metropreneur|last=Evans|first=Walker|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\nOn March 25, Gateway Film Center Lays off a majority of workers due to COVID-19.\n\nOn March 31, Columbus Recreation and Parks/Columbus Metropolitan Library both extend their closure of all locations through May 1 for (Columbus Recreation and Parks) and May 2 for (Columbus Metropolitan Library).<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\nOn April 1, The [[YMCA]] also lays of a majority of its workers.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\nOn April 3, Hocking State Park became the first Ohio state park to close due to COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200404/columbus-area-parks-officials-monitoring-use-as-ohio-closes-hocking-hills-state-park-over-coronavirus|title=Columbus area parks officials monitoring use as Ohio closes Hocking Hills State Park over coronavirus|last=Narciso|first=Dean|website=The Columbus Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/ohio-coronavirus-updates.html|title=Ohio: Latest updates on coronavirus|last=April 2020|first=Stephanie Pappas-Live Science Contributor 04|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n<!--By date?\n[[Columbus Metropolitan Library]] system\n[[Columbus Museum of Art]]\nGovernment, parks, schools, major businesses\nCameron Mitchell https://www.dispatch.com/business/20200319/coronavirus-cameron-mitchell-closes-all-restaurants-creates-relief-fund-for-4500-laid-off-workers-->\n= Gallery =\n<gallery widths=\"140\" heights=\"140\">\nFile:Columbus OH Franklin Park Conservatory.jpg|Columbus Franklin Park Conservatory\nFile:Front Profile Columbus Metropolitan Library 1.jpg|Front View of Columbus Metropolitan Library\nFile:ColsZooMainGate.JPG|Columbus Zoo and Aquarium Main Gate\nFile:Columbus Museum of Art.jpg|Front View of Columbus Museum of Art\nFile:National Veterans Memorial and Museum, Columbus, OH.jpg|National Veterans Memorial and Museum\nFile:COSI in Columbus 1b.jpg|Center of Science and Industry\n</gallery>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Columbus, Ohio}}\n* {{official website|https://www.columbus.gov/coronavirus/}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Ohio|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio|Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Columbus, Ohio|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Health in Ohio]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus outbreak]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "ObliteratedRox", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Columbus,_Ohio"}
{"title_page": "History of the Jews in Galveston, Texas", "text_new": "[[Jew]]s have inhabited the city of [[Galveston]], [[Texas]], for almost two centuries. The first known Jewish immigrant to the Galveston area was [[Jao de la Porta]], who, along with his brother Morin, [[finance]]d the first [[Human settlement|settlement]] by [[European ethnic groups|European]]s on [[Galveston Island]] in 1816.<ref>[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fde78 TSHA Online - Texas State Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> de la Porta was born in [[Portugal]] of [[Jewish]] parentage and later became a [[Jewish Texan]] [[Merchant|trader]].<ref>[http://www.texancultures.utsa.edu/publications/texansoneandall/jewish.htm Jewish Texans<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616033330/http://www.texancultures.utsa.edu/publications/texansoneandall/jewish.htm |date=2010-06-16 }}</ref> In 1818, [[Jean Laffite]] appointed de la Porta [[supercargo]] for the [[Karankawa]] Indian trade. When Laffite left [[Galveston Island]] in 1820, de la Porta became a full-time trader.<ref>http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fde78</ref>\n\n[[Image:New Temple B'nai Israel, Galveston.jpg|thumb|right|New B'nai Israel Synagogue]]\n[[Image:Temple Beth Jacob, Galveston.jpg|thumb|right|Beth Jacob Synagogue]]\n\nIn 1852, residents of Galveston established the first [[Jewish cemetery]] in Texas, with the first organized Jewish services being held in 1856.<ref name=\"tshaonline.org\">http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/ivt01</ref>  During the [[American Civil War]], although most residents had fled the city of Galveston, [[Rosanna Osterman]] remained. In 1862 she opened her home as a hospital, treating first [[Union Army|Union soldiers]] and then extending her care to [[Confederate States of America|Confederate soldiers]].<ref>[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fos08 Handbook of Texas Online - OSTERMAN, ROSANNA DYER<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n[[Congregation B'nai Israel (Galveston, Texas)|Congregation B'nai Israel]] opened in 1868. The congregation was the first [[Reform Judaism|Jewish Reform]] congregation chartered in Texas, and only the second Jewish congregation founded in the state.<ref name=\"tshaonline.org\"/>  On June 20, 1875, the congregation voted to become one of the charter members of the [[Union of American Hebrew Congregations]].\nOne of the pioneers of Reform Judaism in the United States, [[Abraham Cohen Labatt]], moved to Galveston in 1878 and joined the congregation.  He was an active member until his death in 1899.\n\nOn February 15, 1931, two [[Orthodox Judaism|orthodox]] synagogues, The Hebrew Orthodox Benevolent Association and The Young Men's Hebrew Association, merged to become [[Congregation Beth Jacob (Galveston, Texas)|Congregation Beth Jacob]]. Under the leadership of Rabbi [[Louis Feigon]] z'l, the members raised funds to build a new synagogue on the site of the old Hebrew Orthodox Benevolent Association. In the 1970s the congregation joined the [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative Movement]] in an attempt to attract more members. Today the congregation is small, but still active in the Galveston Community.<ref>[http://www.jhvonline.com/default.asp?sourceid=&smenu=96&twindow=&mad=&sdetail=2957&wpage=1&skeyword=&sidate=&ccat=&ccatm=&restate=&restatus=&reoption=&retype=&repmin=&repmax=&rebed=&rebath=&subname=&pform=&sc=1291&hn=jhvonline&he=.com Jewish Herald-Voice<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOne of B'nai Israel's [[rabbi]]s, [[Henry Cohen (rabbi)|Henry Cohen]], helped found the [[Galveston Movement]] in the early part of the twentieth century.  Between 1907 and 1914, the Movement endeavored to divert [[Jew]]s fleeing [[Russia]] and [[eastern Europe]] away from crowded [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] cities.  Ten thousand Jewish [[immigrant]]s passed through [[Galveston, Texas]] during this era, approximately one-third the number who migrated to [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] during the same period.<ref name=\"umg1\">[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/umg01 TSHA Online - Texas State Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  Galveston was chosen as an initial American port of call partly because it was already a destination for [[Germany|German]] shipping company [[Norddeutscher Lloyd]], which operated out of [[Bremen (city)|Bremen]], and because it provided and access to the growing economic opportunities of the American West.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}  Two percent of the total Jewish immigration to the United States occurred via Galveston in 1911, representing 14,000&nbsp;people.  Within several years, however, local merchants began fearing the increased competition, and others were frustrated that [[Polish Jew]]s would not work on Saturday.  Several communities declined to accept more Jewish immigrants.<ref name=\"umg1\"/>\n\nCohen exerted influence on other areas of the community as well. He was instrumental in banishing [[Shakespeare]]\u2019s [[Shylock]] from the Galveston public schools.<ref>[http://www.jewish-history.com/WildWest/jewishstars.html Jewish Stars in Texas<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The community recognized his actions on their behalf, when in 1928 Congregation B'nai Israel commissioned a new facility, which they named the [[Henry Cohen Community House]].<ref name=\"ivt1\">[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/ivt01 TSHA Online - Texas State Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe Jewish community in Galveston welcomed their first native Texas rabbi when [[Jimmy Kessler]] assumed leadership of Congregation B'nai Israel.<ref name=\"ivt1\"/> Kessler later founded the [[Texas Jewish Historical Society]].<ref>[http://www.templebnaiisraelgalveston.org/rab.html Temple B'nai Israel<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Rosanna Osterman]]\n* [[Jonathan Pollard]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Texas|Judaism}}\n* [[History of the Jews in Houston]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Additional references ==\n* [http://www.congregationbethjacob.org/ Congregation Beth Jacob's Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080108130214/http://www.beth-elsa.org/sms043004.htm Article on Jewish Texans by Rabbi Samuel M. Stahl]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041230210654/http://www.jewish-holiday.com/texasstar.html Article on history of Jewish Texans]\n* Goldring/Woldenberg Institute of Southern Jewish Life. \"[http://www.isjl.org/texas-galveston-encyclopedia.html Galveston].\" Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities.\n*Shapiro, Susan. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE4D6173FF93AA15754C0A966958260 IN SHORT: NONFICTION; Home on the Range].\" (about the book ''Pioneer Jewish Texans'') ''[[The New York Times]]''. July 29, 1990.\n{{Galveston, Texas}}\n{{Jews and Judaism in Texas}}\n{{History of the Jews in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Historic Jewish communities in the United States|Galveston]]\n[[Category:History of Galveston, Texas|Jewish]]\n[[Category:Jewish history by city|Galveston]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Galveston, Texas| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[Jew]]s have inhabited the city of [[Galveston]], [[Texas]], for almost two centuries. The first known Jewish immigrant to the Galveston area was [[Jao de la Porta]], who, along with his brother Morin, [[finance]]d the first [[Human settlement|settlement]] by [[European ethnic groups|European]]s on [[Galveston Island]] in 1816.<ref>[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fde78 TSHA Online - Texas State Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> de la Porta was born in [[Portugal]] of [[Jewish]] parentage and later became a [[Jewish Texan]] [[Merchant|trader]].<ref>[http://www.texancultures.utsa.edu/publications/texansoneandall/jewish.htm Jewish Texans<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url