ring the increased competition, and others were frustrated that [[Polish Jew]]s would not work on Saturday.  Several communities declined to accept more Jewish immigrants.<ref name=\"umg1\"/>\n\nCohen exerted influence on other areas of the community as well. He was instrumental in banishing [[Shakespeare]]\u2019s [[Shylock]] from the Galveston public schools.<ref>[http://www.jewish-history.com/WildWest/jewishstars.html Jewish Stars in Texas<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The community recognized his actions on their behalf, when in 1928 Congregation B'nai Israel commissioned a new facility, which they named the [[Henry Cohen Community House]].<ref name=\"ivt1\">[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/ivt01 TSHA Online - Texas State Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe Jewish community in Galveston welcomed their first native Texas rabbi when [[Jimmy Kessler]] assumed leadership of Congregation B'nai Israel.<ref name=\"ivt1\"/> Kessler later founded the [[Texas Jewish Historical Society]].<ref>[http://www.templebnaiisraelgalveston.org/rab.html Temple B'nai Israel<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Rosanna Osterman]]\n* [[Jonathan Pollard]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Texas|Judaism}}\n* [[History of the Jews in Houston]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Additional references ==\n* [http://www.congregationbethjacob.org/ Congregation Beth Jacob's Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080108130214/http://www.beth-elsa.org/sms043004.htm Article on Jewish Texans by Rabbi Samuel M. Stahl]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041230210654/http://www.jewish-holiday.com/texasstar.html Article on history of Jewish Texans]\n* Goldring/Woldenberg Institute of Southern Jewish Life. \"[http://www.isjl.org/texas-galveston-encyclopedia.html Galveston].\" Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities.\n*Shapiro, Susan. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE4D6173FF93AA15754C0A966958260 IN