|-\n| [[Peter Hattrup]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 1984\u20131989, 1994\u20131995, 1997\u20131999, 2001\n|-\n| [[Marcus Hahnemann]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 1994\u20131996, 2012\u20132014\n|-\n| [[Brian Ching]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2001\u20132002\n|-\n| [[Leighton O'Brien]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2001\u20132008\n|-\n| [[Zach Scott]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2002\u2013\n|-\n| [[Roger Levesque]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2003\u20132012\n|-\n| [[W\u00e9lton Ara\u00fajo Melo|W\u00e9lton]] || {{flagicon|BRA}} || 2004\u20132005\n|-\n| [[Taylor Graham]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2005, 2007\u20132011\n|-\n| [[S\u00e9bastien Le Toux]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|FRA}} || 2007\u20132009\n|-\n| [[Kasey Keller]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2009\u20132011\n|-\n| [[Fredy Montero]] || {{flagicon|COL}} || 2009\u20132012\n|-\n| [[Steve Zakuani]] || {{flagicon|COD}} || 2009\u20132013\n|-\n| [[Freddie Ljungberg]] || {{flagicon|SWE}} || 2009\u20132010\n|-\n| [[Blaise Nkufo]] || {{flagicon|SUI}} || 2010\u20132011\n|}\n\n\u00a4 Played for two distinct Sounders franchises\n\n== Honors ==\n=== International ===\n'''[[CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions Cup]]'''\n* '''4th place (1):''' [[1996 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1996]]\n\n=== Domestic ===\n'''[[U.S. Open Cup]]'''\n* '''Winners (4):''' [[2009 U.S. Open Cup Final|2009]], [[2010 U.S. Open Cup Final|2010]], [[2011 U.S. Open Cup Final|2011]], [[2014 U.S. Open Cup Final|2014]]\n* '''Runners-up (1):''' [[2012 U.S. Open Cup Final|2012]]\n\n=== League ===\n==== MLS ====\n'''[[MLS Cup Playoffs]]'''\n* '''Conference Semifinalists (6):''' [[2009 MLS Cup Playoffs#Western Conference|2009]], [[2010 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2010]], [[2011 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference semifinals|2011]], [[2013 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2013]], [[2015 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2015]], [[2018 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2018]]\n* '''Conference Finalists (2):''' [[2012 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Championships|2012]], [[2014 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Championships|2014]]\n*'''Conference Champions (3):''' [[2016 MLS Cup Playoffs#MLS Cup|2016]], [[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#MLS Cup|2017]], [[2019 MLS Cup Playoffs#MLS Cup|2019]]\n* '''Winners (2):''' [[MLS Cup 2016|2016]], [[MLS Cup 2019|2019]]\n'''[[Supporters' Shield]]'''\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[2014 Major League Soccer season|2014]]\n\n==== NASL ====\n'''[[Soccer Bowl]]'''\n* '''Runner Up (2):''' [[1977 North American Soccer League season|1977]], [[1982 North American Soccer League season|1982]]\n\n'''[[Trans-Atlantic Challenge Cup]]'''\n\n* Winner 1981\n\n==== USL ====\n'''[[USL First Division|USL First Division Playoffs]]'''\n* '''Winners (4):''' 1995, 1996, 2005, 2007\n* '''Runners-up (1):''' 2004\n\n'''[[USL First Division|USL Commissioner's Cup]]''' (Best USL Regular Season Record)\n* '''Winners (3):''' 1994, 2002, 2007\n* '''Runners-up (1):''' 1995\n\n=== Other ===\n'''[[Cascadia Cup]]'''\n* '''Winners (6):''' 2006, 2007, 2011, 2015, 2018, 2019\n\n'''[[Heritage Cup (MLS)|Heritage Cup]]'''\n* '''Winners (7):''' 2010, 2011, 2013, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n\n== OL Reign, 2013\u2013present==\n{{main|OL Reign}}\nIn November 2012, it was confirmed that a Seattle-based women's professional soccer team owned by Bill Predmore (founder and CEO of Seattle-based digital marketing agency, POP) had been accepted into a new women's professional soccer league, later named the [[National Women's Soccer League]].<ref name=seattletimes_pr_112112>{{cite news|title=Seattle Club Selected as Founding Member of New Women's Professional Soccer League|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/soundersfcblog/2019731392_seattle_will_have_team_in_new.html|newspaper=Seattle Times|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=seattletimes_11212>{{cite news|title=A stop and chat with Bill Predmore, owner of the new women's pro team in Seattle|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/soundersfcblog/2019731718_a_stop_and_chat_with_bill_pred.html|newspaper=Seattle Times|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> Former general manager of the [[Seattle Sounders Women]] and [[Seattle Sounders FC]] Director of Youth Programs,<ref>{{cite web|title=Amy Carnell, the Sounders FC Director of Youth Programs since 2008, has helped build the largest youth camp system in Major League Soccer.|url=http://www.soundersfc.com/news/articles/2011/12-december/amy-carnell-sounders-women.aspx|publisher=Seattle Sounders FC|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> Amy Carnell, was named General Manager and [[Laura Harvey]] head coach. About a week before the season began, Carnell resigned and Harvey took on many of her responsibilities similar to her role with [[Arsenal Ladies]].\n\nOriginally known as Seattle Reign FC, they played their first season at [[Starfire Sports|Starfire Stadium]] in [[Tukwila, Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bird|first=Liviu|title=Seattle Reign FC announces Starfire Stadium as home venue|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2013/01/23/seattle-reign-fc-announces-starfire-stadium-as-home-venue/|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> The stadium is located approximately 12 miles from downtown [[Seattle]] and is the training facility for [[Seattle Sounders FC]], as well as where the Sounders play their [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] matches.\n\nFor the 2014 season, they moved to [[Memorial Stadium (Seattle)|Memorial Stadium]] on the [[Seattle Center]] grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/soundersfc/2014/02/06/reign-fc-confirms-its-new-home-will-be-seattle-memorial-stadium/ |title=Reign FC confirms its new home will be Seattle Memorial Stadium |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |work=Sounders FC Blog |publisher=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=February 6, 2014 |accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe club's lease on Memorial Stadium ended after the 2018 season, and the club faced a stadium crisis as that date approached. The stadium, owned by the [[Seattle School District]], dates to the 1940s and does not meet facility standards that were to be enforced by the NWSL and the [[United States Soccer Federation]] in 2019. Additionally, the district had announced plans to build a new high school in the area, with the stadium as the most likely site.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/features/will-reign-fc-thrive-or-just-survive-nwsls-cloudy-future-seattle |title=Will Reign FC thrive, or just survive? The NWSL's cloudy future in Seattle |first=Richard |last=Farley |magazine=[[FourFourTwo]] |date=September 27, 2017 |accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> Eventually, Predmore announced in January 2019 that the club would relocate to Tacoma and rebrand as Reign FC. As part of the move, separate minority stakes in the club were purchased by the ownership group of [[Minor League Baseball]]'s [[Tacoma Rainiers]], as well as Sounders FC principal owner [[Adrian Hanauer]] and his mother. Reign now play at [[Cheney Stadium]], home to both the Rainiers and the Sounders' reserve side, [[Tacoma Defiance]]. The Rainiers were already planning to build a new soccer-specific facility for the Defiance next to Cheney Stadium; upon its completion (expected for 2021), both the Defiance and Reign will move there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sounderatheart.com/2019/1/30/18203707/reign-owners-open-letter |title=An Open Letter to Fans and Supporters of Seattle Reign FC from the owners |first=Bill and Teresa |last=Predmore |work=Sounder at Heart |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |date=January 30, 2019 |accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, OL Groupe, the parent company of top-level French club [[Olympique Lyonnais]], purchased a majority stake in Reign FC in a transaction that closed in January 2020. OL Groupe purchased an 89.5% stake in the side; the Predmores retained 7.5%, and former NBA star [[Tony Parker]], a business partner of OL, purchased 3%.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levine |first1=Matthew |title=OL Groupe to become majority owner of National Women\u2019s Soccer League\u2019s Reign FC |url=http://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/ol-groupe-to-become-majority-owner-of-national-womens-soccer-leagues-reign-fc |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |publisher=NWSL}}</ref> The new owners announced the rebranding of the team as [[OL Reign]] on March 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Reign FC Reveal New Name and Brand Identity |url=https://www.olreign.com/news/2020/3/6/reign-fc-reveal-new-name-and-brand-identity |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |publisher=OL Reign |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reign Season-by-Season Results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!League\n!Regular Season\n!Playoffs\n!Avg. Attendance\n|-\n|[[2013 Seattle Reign FC season|2013]]\n|[[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n|7th Place\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2,306\n|-\n|[[2014 Seattle Reign FC season|2014]]\n|[[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n|1st Place\n|Runner-up\n|3,632\n|-\n| [[2015 Seattle Reign FC season|2015]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 1st Place\n| Runner-up\n| 4,060\n|-\n| [[2016 Seattle Reign FC season|2016]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 5th Place\n| ''Did not qualify''\n| 4,602\n|-\n| [[2017 Seattle Reign FC season|2017]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 5th Place\n| ''Did not qualify''\n| 4,037\n|-\n| [[2018 Seattle Reign FC season|2018]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 3rd Place\n| Semifinals\n| 3,824\n|-\n| [[2019 Reign FC season|2019]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 4th Place\n| Semifinals\n| 5,213\n|}\n\n==Seattle Impact==\n{{main|Seattle Impact}}\n\nIn 2014, the [[Major Arena Soccer League]] awarded an expansion to former Tacoma Star player Dion Earl. The '''Seattle Impact''' played its inaugural season at the [[ShoWare Center]]. However, in January 2015, the team was sold to the semi-professional [[Tacoma Stars (2003)|Tacoma Stars]], who completed the season under the Stars' name.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Women's association football}}\n* [[Gorilla FC]]\n* [[OL Reign]]\n* [[Seattle Sounders (1974\u201383)]]\n* [[Seattle Sounders FC results by opponent]]\n* [[Seattle Sounders \u2013 Portland Timbers rivalry|Sounders\u2013Timbers rivalry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n* [http://soundersfc.com Sounders FC website]\n* [https://olreign.com OL Reign website]\n\n{{Seattle Sounders FC}}\n{{OL Reign}}\n{{USSoccer}}\n\n{{Seattle Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of professional soccer in Seattle}}\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders (1994\u20132008)]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders FC]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders (1974\u20131983)]]\n[[Category:OL Reign]]\n[[Category:History of soccer in the United States|Seattle]]\n[[Category:History of Seattle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Citation style|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\nThe '''history of professional soccer in Seattle''' spans over four decades, and includes clubs playing in numerous different leagues such as the [[North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984)|North American Soccer League]], leagues operated by the [[United Soccer League]], the [[Continental Indoor Soccer League]], [[Major League Soccer]], the [[National Women's Soccer League]], and most recently the [[Major Arena Soccer League]].\n\n== Seattle Sounders (1974\u20131983) ==\n{{main|Seattle Sounders (1974\u20131983)}}\n\nOn December 11, 1973, a group of Seattle investors led by Walt Daggatt were granted rights to a franchise in the [[North American Soccer League]], one of three (including the [[Vancouver Whitecaps]] and [[San Jose Earthquakes]]) heralding the expansion of America's struggling top-tier soccer league to the west coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2013/05/19/1974-1983-seattle-sounders-nasl/|title=Seattle Sounders, North American Soccer League|date=May 19, 2013|website=funwhileitlasted.net}}</ref><ref name=\"sounderatheart.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/2014/2/4/5338390/know-your-history-the-40-years-of-sounders-edition|title=Know Your History: 40 Years of Sounders Edition|website=sounderatheart.com}}</ref> With a budget under $500,000, the investors searched existing American and British teams to assemble a coaching squad and assemble a lineup. Longtime NASL All-Star player [[John Best (soccer)|John Best]] was hired as coach and recruited former Everton star [[Jimmy Gabriel]], 1969 NASL MVP [[Pepe Fernandez]], Crewe defender [[Dave Gillett]] and Hartlepool goalkeeper [[Barry Watling]], among others.<ref name=\"sounderatheart.com\"/>\n\nOn January 22, 1974, the team was christened Seattle Sounders, the moniker having won a highly publicized \"name the team\" contest ([[Seattle Mariners]], the eventual name of the city's second baseball team, was a runner-up). The \"lads\" (so-called because the team were largely English players) were introduced to the media and the public in early Spring, announcing they would play their first home game on May 5. At the time, soccer was largely ignored by the national media, and the game was understood and played by a very small percentage of the population; but Seattle's post-war immigrants from Scandinavia and Britain had brought awareness of soccer, and a youth soccer league had started in 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonyouthsoccer.org/50th_anniversary/|title=50th Anniversary - Washington Youth Soccer|website=Washington Youth Soccer}}</ref> Whether professional soccer could work in Seattle was anyone's guess.\n\nThe answer came at the club's inaugural game, when the Sounders took on the [[Denver Dynamos]] in Memorial Stadium, whose capacity of 13000 was considered ample for a sport which had never averaged more than 3000\u20135000 in other American cities. Over 12000 came to the opening match, the start of which was delayed to allow the unexpectedly large walk-up crowd to enter the stands. Longtime Seattle sportswriter [[Royal Brougham]] introduced the team to great fanfare, though he was booed when he chose to sing, \"Take Me Out to the Ballgame\", as Seattle sports fans were still embittered over the loss a few years earlier of the [[Seattle Pilots]] [[Major League Baseball]] team. It appeared Seattle was ready to embrace a different summer sport.\n\nThe Sounders won their home opener 4\u20131, and fans were hooked. By early summer, the Sounders stunned the American sports community by posting the first-ever sellout of a stadium for a soccer game, drawing 13,498 to their game against the defending champion [[Philadelphia Atoms]]. The Sounders proved successful on the field as well, with a 10\u20137\u20133 record, and Barry Watling won Goalkeeper of the Year honors with an astounding 0.80 goals against average. 36000 tickets were printed in anticipation of a home playoff game to be held in Husky Stadium. Despite their winning record, the NASL points system meant Seattle was edged out of the final playoff spot on the last day of the season, and they finished in third place in the highly competitive Western Conference that year.\n\nThe Sounders returned in 1975 with the addition of [[Tottenham Hotspur]] defender and [[UEFA Cup]] winner [[Mike England]] to anchor the defensive midfield. The success of the Sounders and other western teams led other teams to boost their lineups as well, including the signing of [[Pele]] by the [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]]. Memorial Stadium was expanded several times, eventually growing to hold 17,925, and sold out every game; amazingly, it never rained on a Sounders game in this outdoor facility. On the field, the Sounders were one of the league's better teams, posting a 15\u20137 record and making their first playoff appearance at Portland; their 2\u20131 loss in the quarterfinals cemented the [[Portland Timbers-Seattle Sounders rivalry]] which grew to become American soccer's most storied derby. Two [[indoor soccer]] exhibition games were played as a training exercise that winter as well, marking the origins of that version of the sport.\n\nThe Sounders' success helped Daggatt and his partners get the [[NFL]] [[Seattle Seahawks]] franchise, and both teams started play in the [[Kingdome]] in 1976. The first sporting event held at the Kingdome was a Sounders match against the Cosmos on April 9; 58,128 fans packed the Kingdome that day to investigate the new building and get a look at Pele, who scored two goals to lead the Cosmos to a 3\u20131 victory. Important player signings included former English [[World Cup 1966]] star [[Geoff Hurst]] and goalkeeper [[Tony Chursky]] who would lead the league with a 0.91 goals against average. The Sounders also led the NASL in attendance in 1976 with 23,826 fans per match,<ref name=\"homepages.sover.net\">{{cite web|url=http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1976.html|title=The Year in American Soccer - 1976|website=homepages.sover.net|access-date=January 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107061400/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1976.html|archive-date=January 7, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the team held its first home playoff game, a 2\u20131 victory over the rival [[Vancouver Whitecaps]], reaching the Divisional Championships of the [[1976 North American Soccer League season#Playoffs|1976 NASL playoffs]] before falling short on the road to the [[Minnesota Kicks]] 3\u20130.<ref name=\"homepages.sover.net\"/> The Kicks then returned to the Kingdome for [[Soccer Bowl '76]], where they lost before an unsupportive Seattle crowd of 25000 to the [[Toronto Metros-Croatia]].\n\nJimmy Gabriel assumed the coaching duties from John Best in the 1977 season. The club started slowly, losing 7 of their first 11 games; but a 10-5 tear placed them at 14-12 for the season, and fans continued to come out in large numbers, in part to see the team's first homegrown star, Seattle native and 1977 NASL Rookie of the Year [[Jimmy McAlister]]. Upsetting the favored [[L.A. Aztecs]] on the road in the conference final, they then edged them at home 1-0 before 56,000 fans, winning the Pacific Conference Championship and making it to their first ever championship game. Thousands of Seattle fans drove to Portland, the site of [[Soccer Bowl|Soccer Bowl '77]], to see them play the New York Cosmos before an international audience in what was to be Pele's last game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soundercentral.com/museum/1977updates/Soccer+Bowl+1977/soccer_bowl_1977.htm|title=soundercentral.com|website=soundercentral.com}}</ref>\n\n==F.C. Seattle Storm (WSA), 1984\u20131995==\n{{main|Seattle Storm (soccer)}}\nFootball Club Seattle Storm, also known as the F.C. Seattle Storm, was an American [[soccer]] team based in Seattle. F.C. Seattle was a \"super club\" created to provide Seattle players an opportunity to play at a higher level than the local recreational and semi-pro leagues. In addition to playing exhibition matches against top international teams, F.C. Seattle was a member of the short lived [[Western Soccer Alliance]], was a founding member of the [[American Professional Soccer League]] and later spent three seasons in the [[Pacific Coast Soccer League]].\n\n==Seattle SeaDogs (CISL), 1995\u20131997==\n{{main|Seattle SeaDogs}}\nThe Seattle SeaDogs were an [[indoor soccer]] team that played in the [[Continental Indoor Soccer League]] (CISL) from 1995 to 1997. They won the last CISL championship in 1997.\n\n== Sounders (APSL), 1994\u20132008 ==\n{{Seattle Sounders FC sidebar}}\n{{main|Seattle Sounders (1994\u20132008)}}\n\n=== Debate for MLS or APSL club ===\nUpon the incarnation of [[Major League Soccer]], the Seattle metro area was shortlisted for a potentially candidate to host an inaugural MLS club.<ref name=\"bigsoccer\">{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Farrey |title=Big Soccer Surprise: 38,000 To See Match|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940128&slug=1891994 |newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=January 28, 1994|accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> However, when it came time have a petition to sign with the league, the Seattle organizers only managed to secure 1,300 assurances.<ref>{{cite news |title=Soccer Ticket Pledges Exceed 1,300 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940603&slug=1913752 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=June 4, 1994 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> The low numbers were at first claimed to be the result between a ticket campaign between bringing an MLS expansion club to Seattle, and tickets for the [[Seattle Sounders (1994\u20132008)|American Professional Soccer League (APSL) Sounders]].<ref name=\"1994tickets\">{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Farrey |title=Soccer League Rejects Sounders' Plan; Two Will Compete To Sell Season Tickets |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940224&slug=1896933 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=February 24, 1994 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFailing to reach the minimum 10,000-signatures, Seattle was consequently excluded among the first seven cities to be awarded an MLS club.<ref name=\"1994mls\">{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Farrey |title=Seattle Misses First Mls Cut\u2014But Bid Isn't Dead |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940615&slug=1915706 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=June 15, 1994 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> However, in spite of this, the league announced that five more teams were to be announced later that year, with the chance to improve their chances. Subsequently, Seattle MLS organizers began working with the [[University of Washington]] to secure use of [[Husky Stadium]] as a tentative stadium while they pursued the construction of a permanent [[soccer-specific stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Farrey |title=Seattle Gets Boost in Bid For Team\u2014Husky Stadium Might Be Mls Site |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940717&slug=1920841 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=July 17, 1994 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1994, the inaugural MLS season was postponed to 1996. It was then noted that the absence of an \"adequate grass-field facility\" in the region, as well as the presence of the new APSL Seattle Sounders team had thwarted Seattle's MLS franchise bid.<ref>{{cite news |title=Major League Soccer Postponed Until 1996 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19941116&slug=1942150 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=November 16, 1994 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> In the end, Seattle was not among the cities chosen to establish a team during the first season of the MLS.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/463166/US-PRO-SOCCER-TO-BECOME-REALITY-IN-MARCH-OF-96.html|title=U.S. Pro Soccer To Become Reality in March Of '96|date=June 7, 1995|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|accessdate=June 23, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912172606/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/463166/US-PRO-SOCCER-TO-BECOME-REALITY-IN-MARCH-OF-96.html|archive-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Second attempt for MLS franchise ===\n[[File:Aerial of Qwest Field and downtown skyline, 2002.jpg|thumb|Upon completion in 2002, Qwest Field was also designed for soccer, providing separate amenities for soccer teams.<ref name=\"Seattle Post-Intelligencer 2001-07-27\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/othersports/32948_turf27.shtml|title=Showdown looms over turf in new stadium|last=Bruscas|first=Angelo|date=July 27, 2001|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer | accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Qwest Field goes Au Naturel | date=March 19, 2003 | url =http://www.seahawks.com/qwest-field/facts/natural-grass.html | publisher = Seattle Seahawks | accessdate=November 2, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327205918/http://www.seahawks.com/qwest-field/facts/natural-grass.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009}}</ref>]]\n\nDuring the [[1996 Major League Soccer season|debutant MLS season]]; [[Paul Allen]], the owner of the [[Seattle Seahawks|NFL franchise]], worked with the city to build a new football stadium for his team (today [[CenturyLink Field]]). With the possibility of an MLS [[expansion team]] that could be a co-tenant the facility helped drive public support for the stadium effort.<ref>{{cite news |first=Elliott |last=Almond |title=Want A Stadium For Football? Try A Little Soccer |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960511&slug=2328650 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 11, 1996 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> Many state voters supported the referendum to construct the Seahawks Stadium, because it was expected to double as a professional soccer venue.<ref name=\"2000mls\">{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Sherwin |title=MLS team in Seattle no sure bet |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20000510&slug=4020160 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 10, 2000 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> While the stadium problem was being resolved, a new issue arrose. By [[2000 Major League Soccer season|2000]], MLS was veered away from league-operated clubs, towards investor-operated franchises. As result, wealthy individuals would need to step forward for Seattle to obtain an MLS franchise.<ref name=\"2000mls\"/>\n\nIn the early 2000s, MLS announced their intention to have their first expansion since 1998. In 2002, Seattle was once-again listed as a possible market for an MLS expansion team.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Garber says MLS plans to add teams |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20021019&slug=expand19 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=October 19, 2002 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> But in 2004, the two franchises were award to [[Salt Lake City]], and a second franchise to the Los Angeles area, these teams later becoming known as [[Real Salt Lake]] and [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]], respectively. MLS commissioner [[Don Garber]] indicated that Seattle had been \"very close\" to receiving the expansion team, and ended up being third on the list. [[Adrian Hanauer]], then-owner of the United Soccer League's (USL) Sounders (formerly the APSL Sounders), was in discussions with MLS about an estimated payment of $1 million to purchase an MLS franchise, that could be placed in the Seattle area in time for the [[2006 Major League Soccer season|2006 season]].<ref name=\"2006mls\">{{cite news |first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last=Romero |title=Seattle at \"top of list\" for MLS team in 2006 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20040715&slug=mls15 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=July 15, 2004 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhen Seattle was passed over again during the 2006 season (the franchise was awarded to [[Houston Dynamo|Houston]]), Hanauer announced that he would not be able to secure an expansion team without the help of more investors willing to help cover the increasing MLS franchise fees which had grown beyond $10 million by the mid-2000s.<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Massey |title=Seattle's chances for MLS team take a hit |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20050416&slug=sounders16 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=April 16, 2005 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Brian Schmetzer Era ===\nPrior to the beginning of the 2002 campaign, the [[Seattle Sounders (1994\u20132008)|Sounders]] were coming off a dismal performance the previous season. With the firing of Englishmen [[Bernie James]] the Sounders were in need of hiring a new head coach. Hanauer called on [[Brian Schmetzer]], who last coached the indoor club, the [[Seattle SeaDogs]], and asked him if he was interested in the job. Schmetzer agreed and took the job that season. Schmetzer's highlights of his six-year tenure include Pacific Division titles in his inaugural season and the following season. In 2004, during his third year of coaching, he led the Sounders to the A-League championship game where the team ultimately lost to the [[Montreal Impact]]. The next year, in the Sounders debut in the [[USL First Division]], Schmetzer led the club again to the finals, where they successfully defeated the [[Richmond Kickers]] in penalties.\n\nSchmetzer was a finalist for the 2007 coach of the year award. Although the team had started the season 1\u20133\u20134, they went on to claim the Commissioner's Cup for the league's best regular season record. The team also had a 15-game unbeaten run that included MLS opponents in the [[2007 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]]. The Sounders went on to beat the [[Atlanta Silverbacks]] 4\u20130 to win the postseason championship.<ref name=\"Seattle P-I 2007-09-30\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/othersports/333798_sounders01.html|title=After slow start, Sounders win title, ponder future|last=Gaschk|first=Matt|date=September 30, 2007|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== 2002\u201304: Pacific Champions, and run to USL Final ====\nThe Sounders' 2002 season was easily the strongest season for the USL team and arguably the strongest year of all Sounders franchises. In [[Brian Schmetzer]]'s inaugural campaign as Sounders manager, Schmetzer led the club to 23 victories in 28 matches.<ref name=\"2002 sounders season\">{{cite web|last=Litterer|first=Dave|title=The Year in American Soccer, 2002|url=http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/2002.html#aleague|work=American Soccer Archives|accessdate=March 18, 2011|date=May 30, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811085648/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/2002.html#aleague|archive-date=August 11, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2002, the Sounders only lost one regular season match and had four draws.<ref name=\"2002 sounders season\"/> The record results in 107 points for the season, and easily obtaining the Commissioner's Cup by 22 points.<ref name=\"2002 sounders season\"/>\n\nBy earning the Commissioner's Cup, and winning the Pacific Division regular season title, the Sounders earned a direct bye to the Western Conference semifinals (or the quarterfinals) against their [[Cascadia Cup|Cascadian]] rivals, the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (1986\u20132010)|Vancouver Whitecaps]].<ref name=\"2002 sounders season\"/> The first leg in Seattle was a solid start for the Sounders, as they cruised to a 2\u20130 win.<ref name=\"2002 sounders season\"/> The second leg, however, was a disaster. The match ended in a blowout 6\u20132 defeat. The defeat resulted in a 6\u20134 aggregate loss putting a shocking, abrupt end to the Sounders phenomenal season.<ref name=\"2002 sounders season\"/>\n\n==== 2005\u201308: Three years, two titles ====\n[[File:Emerald City Supporters Take 'Em All.jpg|thumb|left|[[Emerald City Supporters]] display at the 2008 home opener.]]\n\nStarting with the [[United Soccer Leagues 2005|2005]] USL Division One season, the Sounders made it a top priority to win the USL postseason championship, especially following their shortcomings in 2004, with a defeat against [[Montreal Impact]]. During their 2005 campaign, Sounders goalie [[Preston Burpo]], was second in the league in goals against average, averaging .85 goals a match.<ref name=\"2005 season\">{{cite web|url=http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/2005.html|title=The Year in American Soccer, 2005|website=homepages.sover.net|access-date=January 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105121200/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/2005.html|archive-date=November 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> That season, defender [[Taylor Graham]] won the league's \"Defender of the Year\" award<ref name=\"2005 season\"/> as well and was named to the \"USL First Division Best XI\" that year, too.<ref name=\"2005 season\"/> In 2005, the Sounders finished in fourth place,<ref name=\"2005 season\"/> and went on to win the championship against the [[Richmond Kickers]] in penalty kicks.<ref name=\"2005 season\"/>\n\nThe following year, 2006, proved to be a rough year for the defending champions, as they failed to qualify for the playoffs, and finished in seventh place in the league table. In the midst of their dismal season, striker [[Cam Weaver]] netted 18 goals for the club, as well as an additional three assists scoring 39 individual points in the USL First Division. He finished the season with the second highest number of points behind [[Miami FC (2006)|Miami FC]]'s [[Romario]]. Weaver was also named the USL First Division's \"Rookie of the Year\". Weaver received some minor international recognition, and subsequently signed with second division-Norwegian club [[FK Haugesund]]. In 2014 he returned to Seattle and played one year for the MLS-side [[Seattle Sounders FC|Seattle Sounders]].<ref>http://www.mlssoccer.com/players/cam-weaver</ref>\n\nAlthough 2007 was highlighted by the announcement of Seattle being award an MLS expansion franchise, the Sounders had a successful USL season, which proved to be their best in club history. First, the Sounders won the Commissioner's Cup, which is an award given the league champion with the best season record, of 16\u20136\u20136. They went on to win the postseason USL Cup, by thrashing Atlanta 4\u20130. In the [[2007 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|2007 U.S. Open Cup]], the Sounders made a semifinal run, before losing to [[FC Dallas]] 2\u20131 in extra time. In the Open Cup quarterfinals, the Sounders thrashed MLS-side [[Colorado Rapids]], 5\u20130, thus making it the largest margin of victory a USL club has ever had over an MLS club in any competition. Beforehand in the early rounds, the Sounders played [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]], [[Portland Timbers]] and [[Phoenix Banat Storm|Banat Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/2007.html|title=The Year in American Soccer, 2007|website=homepages.sover.net|access-date=January 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115005934/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/2007.html|archive-date=November 15, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWith the announcement of the MLS franchise, the USL team would play their last season in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Massey |first=Matt |date=April 18, 2008 |title=Sounders open 2008 USL season, eye MLS in 2009 |page=C3 |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/season-preview-sounders-open-2008-usl-season-eye-mls-in-2009/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref> Midfielders [[Roger Levesque]] and [[Zach Scott]] would transition from the USL to the MLS Sounders after a two-month trial period.<ref>https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2009/03/16/sounders-fc-signs-roger-levesque-and-zach-scott</ref> Schmetzer was a candidate for the head coach position for the MLS Sounders, but the job eventually went to [[Sigi Schmid]], who had previously coached the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] and [[Columbus Crew]]. Schmetzer took the role as the top assistant.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 2008-12-23\">{{cite news|url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2008550617_sounders23.html?syndication=rss|title=Sounders FC hire Brian Schmetzer as top assistant|last=Romero|first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel Romero|date=December 23, 2008|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Modern Day Sounders, (MLS) 2007\u2013present ==\n{{main|Seattle Sounders FC}}\n\n[[File:Drew Carey FIFA World Cup 2006.jpg|thumb|left|TV personality, [[Drew Carey]] became a part owner with the Sounders FC, in a bid to join MLS]]\n\n=== Seattle awarded expansion franchise ===\nFollowing the shortcomings in 2006, the next year, Hanauer teamed up with Hollywood producer [[Joe Roth]] to make another bid for MLS expansion into Seattle. This time, at a fee of $30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ridge |last=Mahoney |title=Sounders bring MLS success in Seattle |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/united/2009-07-28-seattle-sounders_N.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=July 28, 2009 |accessdate=December 5, 2009}}</ref> Paul Allen, whose First and Goal company operated [[Qwest Field]] (formerly Seahawks Stadium), joined the duo later that year, making the fourth bid the most promising yet for the region.<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Smith |title=Gooooal? City may soon have franchise |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/cgi-bin/PrintStory.pl?document_id=2003941033 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=October 11, 2007 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref> During the first week of November 2007, rumors began circulating that MLS would be announcing an expansion franchise into the Seattle market the following week and that the ownership trio had brought on a fourth member: TV personality [[Drew Carey]].<ref name=\"expansion\">{{cite news |first=Larry |last=Stone |title=Big-time soccer coming in 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/cgi-bin/PrintStory.pl?document_id=2004005776 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=November 10, 2007 |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring a press conference on November 13, 2007; it was announced that Seattle had been awarded an expansion club by MLS. The announcement provided a return of [[United States soccer pyramid|top-level]] soccer to Seattle for the first time since the dissolution of its [[Seattle Sounders (NASL)|North American Soccer League (NASL) club]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/its-official-seattle-to-get-mls-team-in-2009/|title=It's official: Seattle to get MLS team in 2009|date=November 14, 2007|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=June 23, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326231212/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/its-official-seattle-to-get-mls-team-in-2009/|archive-date=March 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Laurence |last=Moroney |title=MLS announces expansion in Seattle |date=November 13, 2007 |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/mls-announces-expansion-seattle |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== New crest, same name ====\nOn April 7, 2008; along with the club's colors, badge design and logo, the Seattle MLS franchise announced their club's name. To decide the name, the organization held an online poll to decide the name. Overwhelmingly, supporters voted to retain the \"Sounders\" name, alluding to the past Sounders teams.\n\n\"Seattle Sounders FC\" was announced as the team name on April 7, 2008, along with the team logo, colors, and badge design, in a presentation held at the [[Space Needle]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Matthew |last= Gaschk |title=Sounders FC by fans' acclamation |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/soccer/358051_sounders08.html |newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |date=April 7, 2008 |accessdate=July 19, 2009}}</ref> The \"FC\" in the team moniker stands for Football Club, but the team name is officially Seattle Sounders FC. The badge design resembles a [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|heraldic shield]] and consists of two layers which represent \"the partnership between the ownership, the community, the players and the fans.\"<ref name=\"badge\"/> The logo incorporates the [[Space Needle]], an internationally recognized Seattle landmark. The official team colors are Sounder Blue, signifying the waters of the [[Puget Sound]]; Rave Green, representing the forests of the [[Pacific Northwest]]; and Cascade Shale, representing the [[Cascade Range]] to the east of Seattle.<ref name=\"badge\">{{cite press release |title=Badge and Colors Fact Sheet |date=April 7, 2008 |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2008/04-April/Badge-and-Colors-Fact-Sheet.aspx#comments |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=April 7, 2008}}</ref>\n\nFans chose a name for the team in an online poll held between March 27 and 31, 2008. The initial list of possibilities \u2013 Seattle FC, Seattle Republic and Seattle Alliance \u2013 deliberately did not include Seattle Sounders in order to provide a \"fresh start.\" Despite the names having been selected through fan research and internal committees, the omission of the traditional Sounders name rankled many in the Seattle community.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2008/04-April/Sounders-FC-Rings-True.aspx |title=Sounders FC Rings True |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |first=Frank |last=MacDonald |date=April 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name=team_name>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/collegesports/2004296104_regr21.html |title=NW Briefs: List narrows for Seattle Major League Soccer team names |newspaper=The Seattle Times |first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last=Romero |date=March 21, 2008 |accessdate=March 21, 2008}}</ref> In response to the backlash, the team added a fourth \"write-in\" option for the team name, allowing for any name to be suggested on the ballot.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/soccer/356474_mls26.html |title=Sounders name isn't dead yet |newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |first=Matthew |last=Gaschk |date=March 25, 2008 |accessdate=March 27, 2008}}</ref> Of the over 14,500 votes received for the new team name, 49% of the votes included some form of the name Sounders.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seattle Sounders FC Selected as Team Name |date=April 7, 2008 |url =http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2008/04-April/Seattle-Sounders-FC-Selected-as-Team-Name.aspx |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=July 19, 2009}}</ref> Upon announcing the name, Hanauer acknowledged the significance of keeping with tradition: \"The team playing at the highest level in our region has always been called Sounders. Starting with the NASL and then the USL 1st Division, we now have the chance to create a separate and distinct identity with the new MLS team.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing, the Seattle Sounders |date=April 7, 2008 |url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/04/07/introducing-the-seattle-sounders/ |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Jeffrey |last=Marcus |accessdate=November 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\nTeam ownership revealed the first Sounders FC jersey on May 28, 2008, and announced [[Microsoft]] as the team's sponsor in a five-year deal worth approximately $20 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121194248966725139?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Soccer's Sounders Get a Microsoft Kick |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |last=Futterman |first=Matthew |date=May 28, 2008 |accessdate=May 28, 2009}}</ref> As part of the agreement, the [[Xbox 360]] and [[Xbox Live]] brands appear on the front of Sounders FC's jerseys and throughout the stadium.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2008/05-May/Sounders-FC-Announce-Sponsorship-with-Microsoft-and-Xbox-360.aspx |title=Sounders FC Announce Sponsorship with Microsoft and Xbox 360 |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |date=May 28, 2008 |accessdate=July 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Sigi Schmid Era ===\n\n==== 2009: Inaugural MLS campaign ====\n{{see also|2009 Seattle Sounders FC season}}\n[[File:Seattle Sounders v Red Bull New York kick off.jpg|thumb|right|[[New York Red Bulls]] kick-off to start the 2009 MLS season against Seattle]]\nThe Sounders began their inaugural MLS campaign during the 2009 MLS season. Prior to the opening match, the Sounders sold all 22,000 of their season ticket packages.<ref>{{cite news |first=William |last=Yardley |title=New Soccer Team Stokes Seattle\u2019s Passion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/01/us/01seattle.html?partner=rss&emc=rss |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 31, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2009}}</ref> The 22,000 ticket holders, gave the Sounders a record for the most season ticket holders ever in MLS history.<ref name=\"1stSellOut\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2009/03-March/Home-Opener-Sold-Out.aspx |title=Sounders FC Sells Out Home Opener |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |date=March 2, 2009 |accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref> They played their first home match on March 19, 2009, to a sold-out crowd of 32,523, defeating the [[2008 MLS Cup|2008 MLS Cup runners-up]], [[New York Red Bulls]], by a 3\u20130 margin.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Winner |title=Montero shines as Sounders FC roll |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/montero-shines-sounders-fc-roll |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=March 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> Seattle was the first MLS expansion team to win their first three games, and they did so with a [[Clean sheet|shutout]] in each.<ref>{{cite news |title=Keller ejected as Sounders FC lose for first time |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2009026007_apsocmlswizardssoundersfc.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=April 11, 2009 |accessdate=May 25, 2009}}</ref> [[Fredy Montero]] scored the first regular season goal in team history, finishing a movement from [[Sebastien Le Toux]] and [[Osvaldo Alonso]] in the 12th minute. Montero assisted [[Brad Evans|Brad Evans']] goal, and also scored the team's third goal. [[Kasey Keller]], a veteran American goalkeeper who had played his entire career abroad, made his MLS debut at 39 years of age, and made two saves to register the team's first regular season shutout.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2009/03-March/Game-1.aspx |title=Sounders FC win inaugural game |first=Matt |last=Gaschk |date=March 19, 2009 |work=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=April 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMarch 2009 saw Montero winning ''Player of the Week'' honors for week 1 and Keller for week 2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/seattles-montero-wins-player-week |title=Seattle's Montero wins Player of Week |date=January 23, 2010 |work=Major League Soccer |accessdate=April 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/seattles-keller-week-2-player-week |title=Seattle's Keller is Week 2 Player of Week |date=January 23, 2010 |work=Major League Soccer |accessdate=April 11, 2010}}</ref> Montero won ''Goal of the Week'' for the first two games and was named the ''Player of the Month''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/forward-montero-earns-player-month |title=Forward Montero earns Player of Month |date=January 23, 2010 |work=Major League Soccer |accessdate=April 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter their first two victories at home, Sounders FC played their MLS away fixture against [[Toronto FC]]. The Sounders expected a challenging away environment, but were victorious in a 2\u20130 shutout. Soon after, reports out of Seattle linked Montero to a [[sexual assault]] case with an unidentified woman. In a statement made by Sounders publicist, Montero asserted that the allegations stemmed from a disagreement in which he sought to end the relationship.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2008990345_sounders06.html | work=The Seattle Times | title=Agent defends Sounders FC soccer star Fredy Montero | date=April 6, 2009}}</ref> and a police inquiry resulted in no charges being filed. Seattle Sounders FC suffered their first competitive loss at home against the [[Kansas City Wizards]]. [[Kasey Keller]] was sent off in the 29th minute for a handball outside the 18-yard box, as the Sounders fell 1\u20130 to the Wizards. The following week they lost at [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]]. [[Chris Eylander]] was scored on twice while covering the goal during Keller's suspension. The Sounders again failed to score.\n\nThe Sounders returned to their winning ways in a 2\u20130 home win versus the [[San Jose Earthquakes]].\n\nIt was announced in early July that the Sounders had signed left-footed Costa Rican defender [[Leonardo Gonz\u00e1lez]] to help at the left back position. The position had been a weak spot in Seattle's defense and filled by three separate players throughout the season.<ref name=\"The Seattle Times July 3, 2009\">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2009414215_sounders03.html?syndication=rss|title=Sounders FC signs Costa Rican defender Leonardo Gonzalez|last=Jose|first=Romero|date=July 3, 2009|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, the Sounders hosted the Houston Dynamo at Qwest Field. Brian Schmetzer filled in for Schmid who was at his son's wedding. Ianni scored his first goal of the season on bicycle kick that would earn him the MLS goal of the Week.<ref name=\"ESPN July 12, 2009\">{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=261940&cc=5901|title=Seattle 2\u20131 Houston: Ianni's dramatic winner|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=October 15, 2009}}</ref> On the following Tuesday, the Sounders defeated the Dynamo at Strfire in the U.S. Open Cup semifinals. Houston led when Jaqua scored in the 89th minute. King scored a goal five minutes into [[extra time]], thus sending the Sounders FC to the Open Cup finals against D.C. United.<ref name=\"houston-opencup\">{{cite news|first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last=Romero |title=Sounders beat Dynamo in Open Cup semis, 2\u20131 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2009513240_apsocopencupdynamosounders1stldwritethru.html |work=The Seattle Times |date=July 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604100157/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2009513240_apsocopencupdynamosounders1stldwritethru.html |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2009 the Seattle Sounders lost 0\u20132 in a friendly with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. All sections of the stadium were open and sold out with a crowd of 65,289 in attendance. The game was the first with the team for Chelsea's new manager, [[Carlo Ancelotti]], and their new forward [[Daniel Sturridge]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Gaschk |title=65,000 watch Chelsea FC top Sounders FC 2\u20130 |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/Matchday/Matches/2009/Season/Chelsea.aspx |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |date=July 19, 2009 |accessdate=July 19, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5j0w5HJVu?url=http://www.soundersfc.com/Matchday/Matches/2009/Season/Chelsea.aspx|archivedate=August 14, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe club set a state record for attendance at a soccer match on August 5, 2009, when 66,848 attended a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] with [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Winner |title=Messi shines as Barcelona tops Seattle |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/messi-shines-barcelona-tops-seattle |work=Major League Soccer |accessdate=April 18, 2010 |date=August 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2009, Sounders FC became the second MLS expansion team in league history ([[Chicago Fire (soccer)|Chicago]] was first) to win the [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] tournament in their first season.<ref name=\"opencup\">{{cite news|title=Seattle Sounders FC Become Second MLS Expansion Team to Claim U.S. Open Cup Crown |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2009/09/Seattle-Sounders-Become-Second-Expansion-Team-to-Claim-US-Open-Cup-Crown.aspx |publisher=United States Soccer Federation |date=September 2, 2009 |accessdate=September 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905014508/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2009/09/Seattle-Sounders-Become-Second-Expansion-Team-to-Claim-US-Open-Cup-Crown.aspx |archivedate=September 5, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> They did so by defeating [[D.C. United]] 2\u20131 on the road at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Stadium]].<ref name=\"Charles\">{{cite news |first=Boehm |last=Charles |title=Sounders FC edge United, earn first trophy |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/sounders-fc-edge-united-earn-first-trophy |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=September 2, 2009 |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> In winning the U.S. Open Cup tournament, they qualified for the preliminary round of the [[2010\u201311 CONCACAF Champions League]].<ref name=\"opencup\"/>\n\nOn October 17, 2009, Sounders FC became the second MLS expansion team in league history (again, Chicago had been first) to qualify for the playoffs in their first season. They clinched a playoff berth with a come-from-behind victory over the [[Kansas City Wizards]] 3\u20132 at Kansas City.<ref>{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Rusert |title=Seattle tops Wizards, clinches playoff spot |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/seattle-tops-wizards-clinches-playoff-spot |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=October 17, 2009 |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> Seattle finished the regular season with a record of 12 wins, 7 losses, and 11 ties. The club set a new MLS record for average attendance at 30,943 fans per game.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Winner |title=Home crowd gives Sounders FC big boost |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/home-crowd-gives-sounders-fc-big-boost |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=October 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> Their inaugural season came to an end in the [[2009 MLS Cup Playoffs]] when they lost in the conference semifinals to the [[Houston Dynamo]] with a 1\u20130 aggregate score in a [[Two-legged match|two-legged series]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jeremy |last=Rakes |title=Houston defeats Sounders, takes series |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/houston-defeats-sounders-takes-series-0 |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=November 8, 2009 |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> During the 2009 season, all 15 Sounders FC MLS regular season home matches, their home playoff match, and their 4 home U.S. Open Cup matches (played at [[Starfire Sports Complex]]) were sold out.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel|last= Romero |title=Sounders success story, by the numbers |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2010203684_soundersnumbers05.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=November 4, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108012102/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2010203684_soundersnumbers05.html|archive-date=November 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===== First U.S. Open Cup Title =====\n{{see also|2009 U.S. Open Cup|2009 U.S. Open Cup Final}}\n\n[[File:SoundersUSOpenCup.jpg|thumb|right|Sounders FC captain, [[Kasey Keller]] and midfielder [[Osvaldo Alonso]] hoist the 2009 U.S. Open Cup trophy]]\n\nDuring the Sounders FC first season in MLS, the club won their first ever [[U.S. Open Cup]] title, including any past Sounders franchise. The team was also the first club in modern Open Cup history to win the tournament after playing through a string of qualification propers to enter at the third round proper.\n\nPrior to their first qualification match against [[Real Salt Lake]], Schmid asserted that the Open Cup was extremely critical to the club and that they were playing to win. One of the reasons the club cited, was the opportunity to qualify into the [[CONCACAF Champions League]] upon winning the Open Cup title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/sounders/2009/04/27/sigi_schmid_quotes_4-27-09.html |title=Sigi Schmid quotes, 4\u201327\u201309 |accessdate=January 24, 2009 |first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last=Romero |date=April 27, 2009 |work=The Seattle Times |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5j0w3zkV8?url=http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/sounders/2009/04/27/sigi_schmid_quotes_4-27-09.html |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Sounders FC played U.S. Open Cup home games at the [[Starfire Sports Complex]] in [[Tukwila, Washington]]. The facility is older and smaller than the club's home stadium for league matches, [[Qwest Field]], but Sounders FC representatives preferred the atmosphere at Starfire for smaller cup matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/seattlesports/archives/169659.asp |title=Colorado coach miffed at Sounders' playing facility |accessdate=July 5, 2009 |first=Greg |last=Johns |date=May 7, 2009 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5j0w4PRBg?url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/seattlesports/archives/169659.asp |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the first qualification proper, on April 28, 2009; the Sounders defeated Salt Lake 4\u20131. [[Sebastian Le Toux]] scored two goals, and [[Roger Levesque]] had three [[Assist (football)|assists]] in front of a sold-out crowd at Starfire.<ref>{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Winner |title=Sounders FC defeat RSL in US Open Cup qualifier |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/sounders-fc-defeat-rsl-us-open-cup-qualifier |work=Major League Soccer |date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=April 9, 2010}}</ref> Sounders FC hosted their second qualification match on May 26, 2009, also at Starfire, this time against the [[Colorado Rapids]]. Reserve player [[Kevin Forrest]] scored the only goal in the match as Seattle defeated the Rapids 1\u20130, securing their entry into the third round proper of the official cup competition as one of the eight teams representing MLS.<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Gaschk |title=US Open Cup \u2013 Colorado Rapids Match Report |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/Matchday/Matches/2009/Season/US-Open-Cup-Rapids.aspx |work=Seattle Sounders FC |date=May 26, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most unforgettable matches for the Sounders, was the third round proper fixture against their longstanding rivals, the [[Portland Timbers (2001\u201310)|Portland Timbers]]. Considered their most bitter rival over the past 30 years, it was the first time in four years that any Sounders or Timbers club competed against one another in the Open Cup. Traveling south to [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], the Sounders claimed it would be one of the toughest matches of the entire tournament. In front of a sold-out crowd on July 1, 2009; the Sounders were able to defeat the Timbers 2\u20131, thanks to goals from Levesque and [[Nate Jaqua]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last= Romero |title=Sounders FC cuts down Portland 2\u20131 in spirited battle of Northwest rivals |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2009409566_sounders02.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=July 2, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> The following week, in a quarterfinal match at Starfire, Sounders FC defeated visiting [[Kansas City Wizards|Kansas City]] 1\u20130 on a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] in the 89th minute scored by [[Sebastien Le Toux]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last=Romero |title=Sounders FC earns 1\u20130 victory over Kansas City Wizards in Open Cup |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2009430839_sounders08.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=July 8, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> Three weeks later, on July 21, Sounders FC won their semifinal match 2\u20131 over the [[Houston Dynamo]] at Starfire. Seattle took the lead for good when [[Stephen King (soccer)|Stephen King]] scored a goal five minutes into [[extra time]], sending Sounders FC to the cup final.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last=Romero |title=Sounders beat Dynamo in Open Cup semis, 2\u20131 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2009513240_apsocopencupdynamosounders1stldwritethru.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=July 21, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604100157/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2009513240_apsocopencupdynamosounders1stldwritethru.html |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2009, Sounders FC became the second MLS expansion team in league history ([[Chicago Fire (soccer)|Chicago]] was first) to win the [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] tournament in their first season.<ref name=\"opencup\"/> They did so by defeating [[D.C. United]] 2\u20131 on the road at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Stadium]].<ref name=\"Charles\"/> In winning the U.S. Open Cup tournament, they qualified for the preliminary round of the [[2010\u201311 CONCACAF Champions League]].<ref name=\"opencup\"/>\n\n==== 2010: Second U.S. Open Cup and return to Champions League ====\n{{see also|2010 Seattle Sounders FC season|2010 U.S. Open Cup Final|2010\u201311 CONCACAF Champions League}}\n\n[[File:Sounders FC tifo 2010 03 25.JPG|300px|thumb|alt=Fans in a stadium display a large banner. In the center is a picture of Thor wearing a green jersey and smashing the Union logo. It reads \"Smash the Union\" in the center, \"Seattle\" vertically on the left, and \"Sounders\" on the right.|The [[Emerald City Supporters]] display their [[tifo]] before the first game of the 2010 MLS season at Qwest Field between Seattle Sounders FC and the Philadelphia Union.]]\n\nFor the second consecutive year, the Sounders were chosen to host the opening match of the MLS season, which was held on Thursday, March 25 and nationally televised on ESPN2.<ref name=\"firstkick\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/content/mls-clubs-2010-home-openers-unveiled |title=MLS clubs' 2010 Home Openers unveiled |accessdate=November 23, 2009 |date=September 24, 2009 |publisher=Major League Soccer}}</ref><ref name=\"moreFirstkick\">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2009936517_more_on_first_kick_and_sounder.html |title=More on First Kick and Sounders FC opener at home next year |first=Jose |last=Romero |date=September 24, 2009 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> [[Joe Roth]], Sounders FC Majority Owner stated, \"Being selected to participate in the first match of the season is a testament to the passion and energy of our fans.\"<ref name=\"moreFirstkick\"/> Their opponent was the expansion franchise [[Philadelphia Union]], the league's 16th team as they played in their inaugural match.<ref name=\"firstkick\"/> Seattle won the match 2\u20130 with goals scored by [[Brad Evans]] in the 12th minute and [[Freddy Montero]] in the 43rd minute. The attendance of 36,241 set a team record for an MLS regular-season or postseason game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011445264_sounders26.html |title=Sounders FC opens season with resounding 2\u20130 win |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=March 25, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n2010 started off rough for the Sounders, first with a home loss to [[New York Red Bulls]] on April 2,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011518178_sounders04.html |title=Red Bulls end road blues, stun Sounders FC 1\u20130 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=April 3, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle times |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> and subsequently relinquishing a two-goal lead against defending [[MLS Cup]] champions, [[Real Salt Lake]] at [[Rio Tinto Stadium|Rio Tinto]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011578896_sounders11.html |title=Real Salt Lake gets late tie with Sounders FC, 2\u20132 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=April 10, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> In spite of knocking off Kansas City's unbeaten streak, the same situation would happen against [[FC Dallas|Dallas]], where the Sounders would play to another two-goal draw.\n\nThe following week, on April 17, Seattle returned home to face the undefeated [[Kansas City Wizards]]. The game appeared to be ending a scoreless tie until late substitute Michael Fucito scored his first career goal in 92nd minute of the match off a throw in from Brad Evans. Sounders FC defeated Kansas City 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011634901_sounders18.html |title=Michael Fucito scores in injury time to lift Sounders FC over Wizards |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=April 17, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 24, 2010}}</ref> The following week, Seattle had two road games in a 4-day period. First they traveled to [[Frisco, TX]] to face [[FC Dallas]] on April 22. Steve Zakuani and Fredy Montero scored for Sounders FC while [[Jeff Cunningham]] scored two [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]s for Dallas, the second of which coming in [[extra time]] on a questionable call. The Dallas game ended in a 2\u20132 tie.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011679150_sounders23.html |title=Sounders FC suffers another late-game disappointment, ties FC Dallas 2\u20132 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=April 22, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 24, 2010}}</ref> During the second leg of the road trip on April 25, Sounders FC was defeated 2\u20130 by [[Toronto FC]] at [[BMO Field]]. Seattle conceded their first ever goal to Toronto when [[Dwayne De Rosario]] scored in the 58th minute. He later assisted [[O'Brian White]] on a second goal in the 76th minute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sounders FC loses one early for a change, 2\u20130 to Toronto |first=Larry |last=Millson |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011702875_sounders26.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 3, 2010 | date=April 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSounders FC began May with a tie at home against the Columbus Crew. Steve Zakuani scored an early breakaway goal in the 8th minute to take the lead. However, Seattle's stoppage time problems continued as the Crew's Steven Lenhart scored off a header in the first minute of stoppage time before the half. The game ended 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/smash-and-grab-crew-leave-seattle-point |title=Smash-and-grab Crew leave Seattle with a point |date=May 1, 2010 |work=Major League Soccer |accessdate=May 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707095324/http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/smash-and-grab-crew-leave-seattle-point |archivedate=July 7, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n| GK_nat  = USA| GK = [[Kasey Keller|Keller]]\n| LB_nat  = CRC| LB = [[Leonardo Gonz\u00e1lez|Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n| RCB_nat = USA| RCB = [[Taylor Graham|Graham]]\n| LCB_nat = JAM| LCB = [[Tyrone Marshall|Marshall]]\n| RB_nat  = USA| RB = [[James Riley (soccer)|Riley]]\n| AM_nat  = USA| AM = [[Mike Seamon|Seamon]]\n| DM_nat  = CUB| DM = [[Osvaldo Alonso|Alonso]]\n| LCF_nat = USA| LCF = [[Roger Levesque|Levesque]]\n| RM_nat  = GAM| RM = [[Sanna Nyassi|Nyassi]]\n| LM_nat  = COL| LM = [[Fredy Montero|Montero]]\n| RCF_nat = COD| RCF = [[Steve Zakuani|Zakuani]]\n| caption = The [[2010\u201311 CONCACAF Champions League]] lineup that defeated [[A.D. Isidro Metap\u00e1n|Isidro Metap\u00e1n]] 1\u20130 at home\n}}\nThe following week, on May 8, Sounders FC hosted the Los Angeles Galaxy. Seattle's continued inability to score and their recent trend of defensive breakdowns culminated in an embarrassing 4\u20130 loss to the Galaxy. This was Seattle's worst ever defeat at home and it was played in front of a team record attendance for a regular season match of 36,273 fans.<ref name=\"losangeles\">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011818248_sounders09.html |title=League-leading Galaxy shellacs Sounders FC, 4\u20130 |first=Mayers |last=Joshua |date=May 8, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> Sounders FC newcomer Miguel Monta\u00f1o made his debut with the club in the defeat to the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2011833166_the_silver_lining_in_defeat_mi.html |title=The silver lining in defeat, Miguel Monta\u00f1o's sparkling debut |first=Mayers |last=Joshua |date=May 10, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> The day after the lopsided defeat to Los Angeles, Sounders FC owner Adrian Hanauer announced a refund for all 32,000 season ticket holders for the embarrassment and indicated that changes were in the works for the club.<ref name=\"refund\">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011825202_sounders10.html |title=Sounders FC to pay back fans for poor outing |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=May 9, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThree days later, May 26, the team participated in their first friendly match of the season, winning it 3\u20130 in a shutout against [[Boca Juniors]]. [[Roger Levesque]], [[Pat Noonan]] and Mike Seamon each scored goals, the latter in his debut for the team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayers|first=Joshua|title=Sounders FC blasts Boca Juniors, 3\u20130|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011963273_sounders27.html|accessdate=May 30, 2010|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=May 26, 2010}}</ref> The team ended the month with another 1\u20130 loss on May 29, this one against the [[Colorado Rapids]], on the road; [[Conor Casey]] scored the only goal of the match.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayers|first=Joshua|title=Sounders FC drops 1\u20130 decision at Colorado|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011988398_sounders30.html|accessdate=June 1, 2010|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=May 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSounders FC regrouped from the difficult loss to LA the next week when they visited the New York Red Bulls. Fredy Montero's absence from the starting lineup was a surprising change in the match. Montero, however, was subbed on late in the game and provided the winning goal in the 85th minute for a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011876454_sounders16.html |title=Fredy Montero comes off bench to give Sounders FC 1\u20130 win over Red Bulls |first=Andrew |last=Keh |date=May 15, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> During the first game of the [[Heritage Cup (MLS)|2010 Heritage Cup]] on May 22, the team lost 1\u20130 to the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] at Qwest. [[Chris Wondolowski]] scored 11 minutes in the match, lengthening the \"scoring drought\" for the Sounders FC at home.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayers|first=Joshua|title=Sounders FC can't overcome early San Jose goal, lose 1\u20130|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2011931399_sounders23.html|accessdate=May 30, 2010|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=May 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Steve|title=San Jose hands Sounders FC 2nd consecutive shutout at home|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/stevekelley/2011932026_kelley23.html|accessdate=May 30, 2010|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2011: Third U.S. Open Cup====\n{{see also|2011 Seattle Sounders FC season|2011 U.S. Open Cup Final}}\n\nOn November 22, 2010, Seattle made a trade with the [[Colorado Rapids]] for defenders [[Julien Baudet]] of France and [[Danny Earls]] of the [[Republic of Ireland]] for [[Peter Vagenas]].<ref name=\"Colorado_Trade\">{{cite news |title=Colorado acquire Vagenas in trade with Seattle |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/colorado-acquire-vagenas-trade-seattle |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |date=November 22, 2010 |accessdate=November 22, 2010}}</ref> Also, the list of the ten protected players for the [[2010 MLS Expansion Draft]] was decided by the club. The draft took place on November 24, 2010 when both the [[Portland Timbers]] and [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC (MLS)|Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] sectected ten players from the Major League Soccer teams, including [[Sanna Nyassi]] (who was later traded to Colorado) and [[Nathan Sturgis]] (who was later traded to Toronto) from [[Seattle Sounders FC]].<ref name=\"expansion-draft\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2010-expansion-draft-pick-pick |title=2010 Expansion Draft: pick by pick |author=MLSsoccer.com |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> Vancouver later traded Jamaican international [[O'Brian White]] to Seattle.<ref name=\"obrian_white\">{{cite news |title='Caps pass O'Brian White on to Sounders |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/caps-pass-obrian-white-sounders |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=November 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2010, Swedish club, [[BK H\u00e4cken]] reported that [[midfielder]], [[Erik Friberg (footballer)|Erik Friberg]] completed a three-year deal with the [[Seattle Sounders FC]]. Seattle has completed a deal bringing him over to the Seattle-based club. They also have announced a contract extension with captain Kasey Keller. On December 15, 2010, the Sounders selected [[Chris Seitz]] of the [[Philadelphia Union]] in the [[2010 MLS Re-Entry Draft]].<ref name=\"re_entry_draft_day_2\">{{cite news|title=Wolff, Angel selected in Re-Entry Stage 2 draft |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/wolff-angel-selected-re-entry-stage-2-draft |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |date=December 15, 2010 |accessdate=December 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219135941/http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/wolff-angel-selected-re-entry-stage-2-draft |archivedate=December 19, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The goalkeeper was later traded to [[FC Dallas]] for a fourth round pick of the [[2012 MLS SuperDraft]].<ref name=\"seitz\">{{cite news |title=Sounders draft keeper Seitz, trade him to Dallas |url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/sounders/archives/231874.asp |publisher=Seattle PI |date=December 15, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2010}}</ref> Defender [[Tyrone Marshall]] was also selected in the draft by the [[Colorado Rapids]].<ref name=\"re_entry_draft_day_2\"/>\n\nThe Sounders also competed in two additional competitions during the 2010 season&nbsp;\u2013 the CONCACAF Champions League and the U.S. Open Cup. In the Champions League, Seattle progressed through the preliminary round, beating [[A.D. Isidro Metap\u00e1n|Isidro Metap\u00e1n]] 2\u20131 on aggregate, but was eliminated in the group stage.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2013032175_apsoccdmarathonsounders1stldwritethru.html |title=Fucito's 2 goals boost Sounders past Marathon, 2\u20130 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=September 29, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> In the U.S. Open Cup, Seattle won matches at Portland and at home against the Los Angeles Galaxy and [[Chivas USA]] before reaching the final, which they hosted at CenturyLink Field against the [[Columbus Crew]]. On October 5, 2010, Seattle won the [[2010 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final|U.S. Open Cup final]], 2\u20131, becoming the first team since 1983 to repeat as U.S. Open Cup champions.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/soccerinsider/2010/10/seattle_sounders_defeat_columb.html |title=Nyassi is nice: Seattle Sounders defeat Columbus Crew, 2\u20131, to repeat as U.S. Open Cup champions |first=Steven |last=Goff |date=October 6, 2010 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> The final was played in front of a U.S. Open Cup record crowd of 31,311,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/10/06/nyassi-scores-twice-seattle-beats-columbus/print |title=Nyassi scores twice, Seattle beats Columbus 2\u20131 |first=Tim |last=Booth |date=October 6, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=February 18, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206082916/http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/10/06/nyassi-scores-twice-seattle-beats-columbus/print |archivedate=December 6, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and the victory ensured Seattle's return to the [[2011\u201312 CONCACAF Champions League|Champions League in 2011]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.concacaf.com/page/CL/NewsDetail/0,,12813~2176075,00.html |title=Seattle claims first berth in 2011\u20132012 CCL |date=October 5, 2010 |work=CONCACAF Web Site |accessdate=October 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009025121/http://www.concacaf.com/page/CL/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C12813~2176075%2C00.html |archivedate=October 9, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sounders USOC 2011.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Several players are standing together with three trophies on the ground in front of them|Sounders FC players with the '09, '10, and '11 U.S. Open Cup trophies.]]\n\nThe Sounders began the [[2011 Seattle Sounders FC season|2011 season]] by hosting the opening match of the MLS season for the third straight year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2013723653_for_the_third-straight_year_so.html |title=For the third-straight year, Sounders FC to host stand-alone opener to kick off MLS season |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=December 10, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> The club hosted the Los Angeles Galaxy, and lost 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2014506147_apsocmlsgalaxysoundersfc2ndldwritethru.html |title=Juninho scores as L.A. beats Seattle 1\u20130 |date=March 15, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> On April 22, 2011, in a match against the [[Colorado Rapids]], Seattle's star midfielder [[Steve Zakuani]] suffered a broken leg in a challenge by the Rapids' [[Brian Mullan]], which ended his season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2011-04-23-3553213542_x.htm |title=Sounders' Zakuani has fractured tibia, fibula |date=April 23, 2011 |newspaper=USA Today |accessdate=April 24, 2011}}</ref> Despite setbacks and a slow start to the season (the club won just 3 of its first 10 matches), the Sounders went on to finish the season with the second-best record in the league at 18 wins, 9 draws, 7 losses, and qualified for the playoffs for a third consecutive year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016616996_sounders27.html |title=Give Sounders FC advantage entering Game 1 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 28, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> On October 4, 2011, Seattle won its [[2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final|third consecutive U.S. Open Cup]], becoming the first club to do so in 42 years, as they defeated the Chicago Fire 2\u20130 in front of another tournament record crowd of 35,615 at CenturyLink Field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2011/10/Seattle-Sounders-Claim-Third-Consecutive-Open-Cup-Title.aspx |title=Seattle Sounders Win Third Consecutive Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup in Front of Record Crowd |date=October 5, 2011 |publisher=US Soccer |accessdate=January 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121035705/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2011/10/Seattle-Sounders-Claim-Third-Consecutive-Open-Cup-Title.aspx |archivedate=January 21, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the [[2011 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS playoffs]], Seattle lost its Western Conference semi-final series 3\u20132 on aggregate to [[Real Salt Lake]]. The club dug itself a hole by losing 3\u20130 in Salt Lake, and could only net two goals in the second leg at home.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016674372_sounders03.html |title=Sounders win, come close, but won't move on in playoffs |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=November 2, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSounders midfielder [[Mauro Rosales]] was recognized by the league as the 2011 Newcomer of the Year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016774655_mauro_rosales_named_mls_newcom.html |title=Mauro Rosales named MLS Newcomer of the Year |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=November 15, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2011, Seattle again broke its own league record for average attendance at 38,496. On October 15, 2011, the club hosted the third-largest crowd ever for a single MLS match, as 64,140 attended the final regular season home match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/31/sounders-on-pace-for-eighth-largest-mls-playoff-crowd/ |title=Sounders on pace for eighth-largest MLS playoff crowd? |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 31, 2011 |newspaper=The Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=January 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103162515/http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/31/sounders-on-pace-for-eighth-largest-mls-playoff-crowd/# |archive-date=January 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the [[2011\u201312 CONCACAF Champions League]], the club finished second in its group and advanced to the knockout round, which was played starting in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016541574_sounders19.html |title=Sounders lose 2\u20131 in group finale but advance to CONCACAF quarterfinals |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 18, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016337794_sounders28.html |title=Alonso's goals let Sounders advance in CONCACAF Champions League |date=September 27, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In champions league group play, Seattle became only the second MLS team in history to win a competitive match in Mexico, defeating [[CF Monterrey]] 1\u20130 on August 23, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2015994626_sounders24.html |title=Sounders FC pulls off historic win in Mexico, beating Monterrey, 1\u20130 |date=August 23, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2012: First trophy-less campaign====\n{{see also|2012 Seattle Sounders FC season|2012 U.S. Open Cup Final}}\nSeattle opened the [[2012 Seattle Sounders FC season|2012 season]] with a run of five straight wins in April and May,<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=May 13, 2012 |title=Sounders FC's win streak comes to end with 1-0 loss to Real Salt Lake |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2018198743_sounders13.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> but fell into a month-long, nine-match winless streak in June. The winless streak ended in a match on July 7, which saw the return of Steve Zakuani from rehabilitation, against the Colorado Rapids.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=July 8, 2012 |title=Sounders snap their winless streak |page=C1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-snap-their-winless-streak-steve-zakuani-returns/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> Seattle reached the [[2012 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final|U.S. Open Cup Final]] for the fourth consecutive year, becoming the first team to do so since 1937,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2012/07/Sporting-Kansas-City-and-Seattle-Sounders-Advance-to-US-Open-Cup-Final.aspx |title=Sporting Kansas City, Seattle Sounders FC Advance to 2012 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final |date=July 11, 2012 |publisher=US Soccer Federation |accessdate=November 26, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715011535/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2012/07/Sporting-Kansas-City-and-Seattle-Sounders-Advance-to-US-Open-Cup-Final.aspx |archivedate=July 15, 2012 }}</ref> but lost to [[Sporting Kansas City]] in a penalty shootout after a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brewer |first=Jerry |date=August 9, 2012 |title=Sounders' quest for fourth U.S. Open Cup ends in penalty-kick loss |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/jerrybrewer/2018879038_brewer09.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> In Champions League group play, the team advanced to the knockout round with four straight wins, each including a goal from [[Sammy Ochoa]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Oshan |first=Jeremiah |date=October 25, 2012 |title=CCL: Estrada, Ochoa prove a dynamite duo for Sounders |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2012/10/26/ccl-estrada-ochoa-prove-dynamite-duo-sounders |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> The Sounders finished third in the Western Conference and qualified for the playoffs, where they advanced out of the first round for the first time in the team's history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=November 9, 2012 |title=Sounders beat Real Salt Lake 1-0, advance in playoffs for first time |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2019640873_sounders09.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> In the Conference Championship, Seattle fell 3\u20130 to Los Angeles in the first leg and came within one goal of tying the series on aggregate before letting an [[away goal]], winning the second leg 2\u20131 but losing 4\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=November 19, 2012 |title=Sounders FC comes up short against Galaxy |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2019711643_sounders19.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> The 2012 season ended without a major trophy for the Sounders, for the first time in their MLS history, and the team failed to qualify for the [[2013\u201314 CONCACAF Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=November 20, 2012 |title=Sounders will get to work shaping 2013 roster |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2019716548_sounders20.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> The top scorer in league play was 28-year-old striker [[Eddie Johnson (American soccer)|Eddie Johnson]], who scored 14 goals in his first season with the club; he earned [[MLS Comeback Player of the Year Award|Comeback Player of the Year]] honors for his performance, which came after unsuccessful loans to European clubs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=November 27, 2012 |title=Sounders forward Eddie Johnson named MLS Comeback Player of the Year |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/sports/sounders-forward-eddie-johnson-named-mls-comeback-player-of-the-year/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== 2013: Arrival of Clint Dempsey ====\n{{see also|2013 Seattle Sounders FC season}}\nDuring the 2013 preseason, the Sounders signed their first [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player]], right back [[DeAndre Yedlin]],<ref>{{cite press release |date=January 11, 2013 |title=Sounders FC Signs First Homegrown Player |url=https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2013/01/11/sounders-fc-signs-first-homegrown-player |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> veteran defender [[Djimi Traor\u00e9]],<ref>{{cite news |date=February 23, 2013 |title=Sounders FC Signs Djimi Traore |url=https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2013/02/23/sounders-fc-signs-djimi-traore |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> and forward [[Obafemi Martins]], who bought his [[release clause]] from his Spanish club.<ref>{{cite news |last=Okeleji |first=Oluwashina |date=March 12, 2013 |title=Obafemi Martins relieved to complete Seattle transfer |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/21757361 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> Longtime forward Fredy Montero left Seattle on loan to Colombian club [[Millonarios F.C.]] in January and,<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=January 21, 2013 |title=Sounders officially loan Montero to Colombian champion Millonarios |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2020185180_sounders22.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> by July, was loaned to [[Sporting CP]] in Portugal with an option to buy; Montero was sold permanently to Sporting in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 30, 2014 |title=Portuguese club Sporting CP complete transfer of former Seattle Sounders forward Fredy Montero |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2014/01/30/portuguese-club-sporting-cp-complete-transfer-former-seattle-sounders-forward-fredy |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> The Sounders began the [[2013 Seattle Sounders FC season|2013 season]] with the [[2012\u201313 CONCACAF Champions League championship stage|knockout round]] of the 2012\u201313 Champions League, facing Mexican club [[Tigres UANL]] in the quarterfinals. After losing 1\u20130 in the away leg and conceding an [[away goal]] in the return leg, the Sounders scored three unanswered goals in the second half to win 3\u20131 and advance to the semifinals. With the win, the Sounders became the first MLS team to eliminate a Mexican team in the knockout stage of CONCACAF Champions League.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=March 13, 2013 |title=Traor\u00e9 screamer helps Sounders to historic comeback against Tigres |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/mar/13/traore-seattle-sounders-tigres-concacaf-champions-league |work=The Guardian |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> Seattle once again played Santos Laguna in the semifinal, but failed to advance after losing 1\u20130 at home and drawing 1\u20131 in [[Torre\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=April 10, 2013 |title=Seattle Sounders eliminated from CONCACAF Champions League by Santos Laguna |page=C3 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2020743819_sounders10.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Sounders began the MLS season with a run of five matches without a win, the worst start in the team's history, due to injuries to key players.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=April 17, 2013 |title=Sounders hope history of rebounds repeats itself |page=C2 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2020793448_sounders17.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> The Sounders failed to advance in the U.S. Open Cup after losing to second-division [[Tampa Bay Rowdies]] in the third round, marking the end of the team's seven-year streak of appearances in the later rounds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=May 31, 2013 |title=Sounders left speechless with recent tough losses |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2021090777_sounders31.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> As players returned to the team, Seattle improved to a six-win, four-loss record in 14 matches by late June.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=June 22, 2013 |title=Sounders hoping to continue turnaround at Real Salt Lake |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2021243701_sounders22xml.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In August 2013, the Sounders completed the signing of [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. national team]] captain [[Clint Dempsey]] from [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] for $9&nbsp;million, the largest transfer deal in the league's history, and a record salary of $32&nbsp;million over four years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Straus |first=Brian |date=August 2, 2013 |title=Shocking transfer has Dempsey headed to Seattle Sounders |work=Sports Illustrated |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/20130802/clint-dempsey-transfer-mls-seattle-sounders-tottenham-hotspur/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806040157/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/20130802/clint-dempsey-transfer-mls-seattle-sounders-tottenham-hotspur/ |archivedate=August 6, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref> The team's continued run of wins put them into Supporters' Shield contention in September, coming within one point of the league-leading Red Bulls,<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=September 23, 2013 |title=Supporters' Shield well within Sounders' reach in final stretch |page=C2 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2021878118_sounders23xml.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> but fell to fourth place in the conference after a run of four straight losses in October.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=October 21, 2013 |title=Sounders clinch a playoff berth thanks to help from Galaxy |page=C2 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2022091784_sounders21xml.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=October 29, 2013 |title=Playoffs mean new start for Sounders |page=C1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2022143889_sounders29xml.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> The Sounders beat the Colorado Rapids 2\u20130 in the knockout round, and drew rivals Portland in the conference semifinal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moschetti |first=Mark |date=October 31, 2013 |title=Sounders survive, advance in playoffs |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2013/oct/31/sounders-survive-advance-in-playoffs/ |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref> Seattle fell 2\u20131 to the Timbers in the home leg and were defeated 3\u20132 in Portland, knocking the Sounders out in a performance that failed to live up to expectations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=November 8, 2013 |title=Sounders' season of title hopes ends in playoff defeat to Portland |page=C4 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2022215333_sounders08xml.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Sounders continued to break the MLS average attendance record for the fourth and fifth consecutive year in 2012 and 2013, with an average of 43,144 and 44,038, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gaschk |first=Matt |date=October 29, 2013 |title=Seattle breaks attendance record for fifth straight season |url=https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2013/10/29/seattle-breaks-attendance-record-fifth-straight-season |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref> The higher attendances were helped by the opening of additional sections in the Hawks' Nest,<ref>{{cite news |date=November 17, 2011 |title=Sounders' Hawks Nest tickets go on sale |page=C7 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> as well as the opening of the upper deck of CenturyLink Field for select regular matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gaschk |first=Matt |date=September 11, 2013 |title=Another massive crowd expected at CenturyLink Field on Friday |url=https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2013/09/11/another-massive-crowd-expected-centurylink-field-friday |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref> The August 25, 2013, home match against the Portland Timbers drew a crowd of 67,385, the second-largest standalone attendance in league history.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 26, 2013 |title=Eddie Johnson gives Sounders 1-0 win over Timbers |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mls/2013/08/26/eddie-johnson-seattle-sounders-portland-timbers/2698441/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014: First MLS Supporters' Shield and Fourth U.S. Open Cup====\n{{see also|2014 Seattle Sounders FC season|2014 U.S. Open Cup Final}}\n\nAfter a disappointing 2013 season, the Sounders replaced starting goalkeeper Michael Gspurning with Toronto's [[Stefan Frei]]. Several veteran players, including Eddie Johnson, Patrick Ianni, Jhon Kennedy Hurtado, Mauro Rosales, and Steve Zakuani, left the club as part of a major restructure; [[Brad Evans]] was named as club captain.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=November 20, 2014 |title=How Sigi Schmid saved his job and moved the Sounders forward |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/sounders/2025067300_sounders21xml.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> [[Marco Pappa]], an experienced MLS player and Guatemalan international, was added to the team. Homegrown player [[DeAndre Yedlin]] was transferred overseas to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 13, 2014 |title=Tottenham confirm signing of DeAndre Yedlin on four-year contract |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/13/deandre-yedlin-signs-tottenham-hotspur-seattle-sounders |work=The Guardian |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Sounders advanced to the [[2014 U.S. Open Cup Final]] and defeated the [[Philadelphia Union]] in [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]], to win their fourth trophy of the tournament. On October 25, 2014, the final game of the 2014 regular season, the Sounders defeated the LA Galaxy 2\u20130 to secure and win their first [[Supporters' Shield]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Bird |first=Liviu |date=October 25, 2014 |title=Pappa's brace carries Sounders to Supporters' Shield win over Galaxy |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/planet-futbol/2014/10/25/marco-pappa-two-goals-sounders-supporters-shield-win-over-galaxy |magazine=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nEntering the playoffs as the top seed, Seattle defeated FC Dallas on the [[away goals rule]] and advanced to the Western Conference Championship to face the LA Galaxy once again. The Sounders lost on [[aggregate score]] and the away goals rule after losing 1\u20130 away and winning 2\u20131 at home. LA would go on to win the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lilgenwall |first=Ari |date=December 18, 2014 |title=2014 in Review: Seattle Sounders enjoy historic season, but fall just short of reaching MLS Cup |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/year-in-review/2014/seattle-sounders-fc |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227050554/http://www.mlssoccer.com/year-in-review/2014/seattle-sounders-fc |archivedate=December 27, 2014 |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2015: Continued playoff frustration ====\n{{see also|2015 Seattle Sounders FC season}}\n\nFormer [[Real Salt Lake]] general manager [[Garth Lagerwey]] was hired by the club in January 2015, replacing Adrian Hanauer.<ref name=\"Lagerwey\">{{cite news |last=Kamrani |first=Christopher |date=January 6, 2015 |title=As expected, Garth Lagerwey named GM of Seattle Sounders |url=http://www.sltrib.com/sports/2027384-155/real-salt-lake-as-expected-garth |work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]] |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSeattle was unable to repeat their successes in the 2014 season. The season started successfully, with several key wins that saw the team at the top of the Western Conference by June.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parchman |first=Will |date=November 11, 2015 |title=2015 In Review: Sounders FC began season with a bang |url=http://www.soundersfc.com/post/2015/11/10/2015-review-sounders-fc-began-season-bang |publisher=SoundersFC.com |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> During a [[2015 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup]] match against the Portland Timbers on June 16, however, Obafemi Martins left the game with a groin injury and Clint Dempsey was suspended after tearing a referee's pocketbook, though he would be called away for the [[2015 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Blue |first=Molly |date=June 19, 2015 |title=Seattle Sounders meltdown vs. Portland Timbers: What's next for Clint Dempsey? |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/timbers/index.ssf/2015/06/seattle_sounders_meltdown_vs_p.html |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Scott |first=Nate |date=June 19, 2015 |title=MLS hits Clint Dempsey with a 3-game suspension for ripping ref's notebook |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/06/mls-hits-clint-dempsey-with-a-3-game-suspension-for-ripping-refs-notebook |work=USA Today |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe injury and suspension of the team's main attacking duo led to a death spiral during the summer, with Seattle winning only one match in nine games. By late August, Martins had recovered and led the team to an 8-match unbeaten streak to secure a playoff spot, finishing 4th in the Western Conference. The Sounders had also successfully topped their group in the [[2015\u201316 CONCACAF Champions League]], beating the Vancouver Whitecaps and [[Club Deportivo Olimpia]], with two wins, one draw, and one loss.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 23, 2015 |title=Seattle Sounders, LA Galaxy through to CCL knockout round |url=http://www.espnfc.com/concacaf-champions-league/story/2629233/seattle-sounders-la-galaxy-through-to-ccl-knockout-round |work=ESPN FC |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> [[Paraguay]]an international [[Nelson Haedo Valdez]] was signed as the club's newest [[Designated Player Rule|designated player]], and was joined by fellow international signings [[Andreas Ivanschitz]] and [[Rom\u00e1n Torres]] in August 2015;<ref>{{cite news |last=Ruiz |first=Don |date=August 15, 2015 |title=Sounders to sport new look against Orlando |url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/soccer/mls/sounders-fc/article31221407.html |work=The News Tribune |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> [[Erik Friberg (footballer)|Erik Friberg]] also returned to the club after his stint in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=July 22, 2015 |title=Sounders happy with immediate impact from Erik Friberg |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-happy-with-immediate-impact-from-erik-friberg/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the playoff's opening knockout round, the Sounders defeated the LA Galaxy 3\u20132, ending a \"curse\" for the club, who had lost to LA in each of the three previous playoff matchups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Stephen |date=October 28, 2015 |title=Sounders exorcise playoff demons, move past Galaxy in thrilling knockout round victory |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/sounders/article/Sounders-vs-Galaxy-6597229.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> The playoff run would end in the next round, the Western Conference semifinals against FC Dallas, during a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] after both teams were tied on [[aggregate score]] after [[extra time]] in Frisco, Texas.<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Kyle |date=November 8, 2015 |title=FC Dallas oust Sounders on penalties to reach West final |url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/inside-mls/mls-playoffs-conference-semifinals-second-leg-fc-dallas-seattle-sounders-recap-110815 |publisher=FOX Sports |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Liljenwall |first=Ari |date=December 15, 2015 |title=\n2015 MLS Year in Review: Seattle Sounders |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/year-review/2015/seattle-sounders |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Adrian Hanauer was made majority owner of the club, succeeding Joe Roth.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=November 12, 2015 |title=Adrian Hanauer is the new majority owner of the Seattle Sounders |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/adrian-hanauer-is-the-new-majority-owner-of-the-seattle-sounders/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> The club set a new attendance record during the 2015 season, with an average attendance of 44,247.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 26, 2015 |title=MLS sets new attendance records, Seattle hold highest average in league |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/26/mls-sets-new-attendance-records-seattle-hold-highest-average-league |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016: Departure of Schmid ====\n{{see also|2016 Seattle Sounders FC season}}\nPrior to the 2016 season, Obafemi Martins abruptly left the club to sign with [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.]] in the [[Chinese Super League]],<ref>{{cite news |date=February 18, 2016 |title=Obafemi Martins leaves MLS for Chinese Super League |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35573893 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> a move that would hamper the Sounders' offense during the season. The move was mitigated somewhat by the signing of homegrown product [[Jordan Morris (soccer)|Jordan Morris]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=January 21, 2016 |title=Seattle Sounders officially unveil Jordan Morris as Homegrown Player signing |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/seattle-sounders-officially-unveil-jordan-morris-as-homegrown-player-signing/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> GM Lagerwey also traded [[Marco Pappa]] and [[Lamar Neagle]] to other clubs in the offseason.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=July 23, 2016 |title=Seattle running out of patience with Schmid and floundering Sounders |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-soccer-baxter-20160723-snap-story.html |work=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first half of the 2016 season, the Sounders failed to meet expectations, placing near the bottom of the league with 6 wins, 12 losses, and 2 draws. After a 3\u20130 loss on July 24 to Sporting Kansas City, in which the Sounders had only one shot,<ref>{{cite news |last=McDowell |first=Sam |date=July 24, 2016 |title=Sounders limited to one shot in 3-0 loss at Sporting Kansas City |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-limited-to-one-shot-in-3-0-loss-at-sporting-kansas-city/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> Schmid left the club on mutual terms.<ref name =\"sigi\">{{cite news |last=Straus |first=Brian |date=July 26, 2016 |title=Little choice for Seattle Sounders to oust Sigi Schmid, change course |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2016/07/26/sigi-schmid-fired-seattle-sounders-mls-garth-lagerwey |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Brian Schmetzer Era ===\n\n====2016: Comeback and MLS Cup====\n{{see also|MLS Cup 2016}}\nLong-time assistant coach [[Brian Schmetzer]] was named interim head coach upon Schmid's departure.<ref name=\"sigi\" /> The next day, the club announced their signing of Uruguayan midfielder [[Nicol\u00e1s Lodeiro]] on a designated player contract,<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=July 27, 2016 |title=Sounders sign Uruguayan attacking midfielder Nicolas Lodeiro to Designated Player contract |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-sign-uruguayan-attacking-midfielder-nicolas-lodeiro-to-designated-player-contract/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> as well as the return of former designated player [[\u00c1lvaro Fern\u00e1ndez (Uruguayan footballer)|\u00c1lvaro Fern\u00e1ndez]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=July 30, 2016 |title=New signings Nicolas Lodeiro and Alvaro Fernandez both available for Sounders against Galaxy on Sunday |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/new-signings-nicolas-lodeiro-and-alvaro-fernandez-both-available-for-sounders-against-galaxy-on-sunday/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> Despite the sluggish start as well as the loss of midfielder [[Clint Dempsey]], who was forced in August to stop playing after evaluations for an irregular heartbeat,<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=September 27, 2016 |title=Sounders forward Clint Dempsey ruled out for the remainder of this season |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-forward-clint-dempsey-ruled-out-for-the-remainder-of-this-season/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 4, 2017}}</ref> the Sounders rose from ninth place to fourth place in the Western Conference and qualified for the [[2016 MLS Cup Playoffs]], with eight wins, two losses, and four draws. Schmetzer was named as permanent head coach as a result.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=November 2, 2016 |title=Sounders remove interim tag, hire coach Brian Schmetzer on a full-time basis |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-remove-interim-tag-hire-coach-brian-schmetzer-on-a-full-time-basis/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sounders Victory Rally on 4th Avenue.jpg|thumb|The victory parade for the Sounders after [[MLS Cup 2016]]]]\n\nAt the end of the regular season, Jordan Morris was named the [[MLS Rookie of the Year]] after scoring the most goals of any American rookie in MLS (12),<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=November 10, 2016 |title=Sounders forward Jordan Morris named MLS Rookie of the Year |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-forward-jordan-morris-named-mls-rookie-of-the-year/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 4, 2017}}</ref> and Nicol\u00e1s Lodeiro was named [[MLS Newcomer of the Year Award|MLS Newcomer of the Year]] for his 4 goals and 8 assists in 13 appearances.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=November 21, 2016 |title=Sounders midfielder Nicolas Lodeiro named MLS Newcomer of the Year |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-midfielder-nicolas-lodeiro-named-mls-newcomer-of-the-year/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 4, 2017}}</ref> The Sounders advanced from the Knockout Round of the playoffs through a 1\u20130 win over [[Sporting Kansas City]], and beat [[FC Dallas]] 4\u20132 on aggregate to return to the Conference Final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosano |first=Nicholas |date=October 28, 2016 |title=Seattle Sounders 1, Sporting KC 0 &#124; 2016 MLS Cup Playoffs Match Recap |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/10/28/seattle-sounders-1-sporting-kc-0-2016-mls-cup-playoffs-match-recap |work=MLSSoccer.com |accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rodriguez|first=Alicia |date=November 6, 2016 |title=FC Dallas 2, Seattle Sounders 1 &#124; 2016 MLS Cup Playoffs Match Recap |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/11/06/fc-dallas-2-seattle-sounders-1-2016-mls-cup-playoffs-match-recap |work=MLSSoccer.com |accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> The Sounders then defeated the [[Colorado Rapids]] 3\u20131 on aggregate in the final, clinching a spot in their first-ever MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosano |first=Nicholas |date=November 27, 2016 |title=Seattle Sounders reach first MLS Cup with win over Colorado Rapids |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/11/27/seattle-sounders-reach-first-mls-cup-win-over-colorado-rapids |work=MLSSoccer.com |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> On December 10, 2016, the Sounders defeated [[Toronto FC]] 5\u20134 in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]], to win [[MLS Cup 2016]], their first MLS championship in franchise history, going the whole match without a shot on goal.<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Seattle Sounders defeat Toronto FC in shootout to win MLS Cup 2016\n | date=December 10, 2016 | first1=Sam | last1=Stejskal | work=MLS\n | url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/12/10/seattle-sounders-defeat-toronto-fc-shootout-win-mls-cup-2016\n | accessdate=December 11, 2016 }}</ref> The team's performance was called a \"[[cinderella (sports)|cinderella season]]\" and hailed as one of the most dramatic MLS seasons to date.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Caitlin |date=December 14, 2016 |title=There's never been a comeback like the Seattle Sounders' in MLS |url=https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/theres-never-comeback-like-seattle-sounders-mls-120916 |work=Fox Sports |accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017: Falling short of repeat====\n{{see also|2017 Seattle Sounders FC season|MLS Cup 2017}}\nThe Sounders began their title defense with the signings of two academy graduates and several veteran players from MLS and abroad.<ref>{{cite news |last=Miles |first=Todd |date=December 1, 2017 |title=3 biggest reasons the Sounders are back in the MLS Cup |url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/soccer/mls/sounders-fc/article187641083.html |work=[[The News Tribune]] |location=Tacoma, Washington |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> Dempsey also returned from his hiatus and scored in his first match before being called up to the U.S. national team for World Cup qualification.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=March 4, 2017 |title=Clint Dempsey scores in return to lineup, but Sounders drop season opener |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/clint-dempsey-scores-in-return-to-lineup-but-sounders-drop-season-opener/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> The season began with only five wins in the first 17 matches, but was followed by a 13-match unbeaten streak and additional wins to clinch a second-place spot in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=August 11, 2017 |title=Sounders enter first-place showdown with Sporting KC healthy and riding 7-game unbeaten streak |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-head-in-to-first-place-showdown-confident-in-team-theyve-shaped/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Brennan |date=September 23, 2017 |title=Sounders' 13-match unbeaten streak comes to end with 2\u20130 loss to Real Salt Lake |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-13-match-unbeaten-streak-comes-to-end-with-2-0-loss-to-real-salt-lake/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 22, 2017 |title=Defending MLS champion Seattle Sounders claim No. 2 playoff seed in West |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mls/2017/10/22/nicolas-lodeiro-scores-twice-sounders-beat-rapids/106919348/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> In the playoffs, the Sounders beat the Vancouver Whitecaps and Houston Dynamo to win the Western Conference and return to the [[MLS Cup 2017|MLS Cup]], once again facing Toronto at BMO Field.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mahoney |first=Ridge |date=December 8, 2017 |title=MLS Cup Preview: Title game matches up tactics and toughness |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/76003/mls-cup-preview-title-game-matches-up-tactics-and.html |work=[[Soccer America]] |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> Seattle lost 2\u20130 to Toronto, who clinched the first domestic [[treble (association football)|treble]] in MLS history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Jozy Altidore has last laugh to seal MLS Cup glory for Toronto FC |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/dec/09/jozy-altidore-mls-cup-glory-toronto-fc-seattle-sounders |work=The Guardian |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018: Longest winning streak====\n{{see also|2018 Seattle Sounders FC season}}\nSeattle began the 2018 season with a run to the quarterfinals of the CONCACAF Champions League, where they lost 3\u20131 on aggregate to eventual champions [[C.D. Guadalajara]]. During the Round of 16, Jordan Morris injured his [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] and was deemed unfit to play for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=February 26, 2018 |title=Sounders striker Jordan Morris out for the season with ACL injury |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-striker-jordan-morris-out-for-the-season-with-acl-injury/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 18, 2018}}</ref> Without Morris and several injured starting players, the Sounders lost nine of their first 15 matches and were placed bottom of the Western Conference by June. The club signed a new Designated Player, Peruvian forward [[Ra\u00fal Ruid\u00edaz]], that month and began a long unbeaten streak that resulted in a playoff position in late August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=August 14, 2018 |title=Forget the playoffs, Sounders now have a shot at a first-round bye |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/forget-the-playoffs-sounders-now-have-a-shot-at-a-first-round-bye/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=August 18, 2018 |title=Sounders move into playoff territory with record rout of Galaxy |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-move-into-playoff-territory-with-record-rout-of-galaxy/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, the club broke the MLS record for most consecutive wins in the post-shootout era, having won eight consecutive matches. They then extended that win streak to nine games as they beat Vancouver 2\u20131 on September 15, before eventually losing to the Philadelphia Union on September 19.<ref>{{cite news |last=Liljenwall |first=Ari |date=September 19, 2018 |title=Amazed at nine-game winning streak, Sounders not ready to talk history yet |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/09/19/amazed-nine-game-winning-streak-sounders-not-ready-talk-history-yet-story.html |agency=Major League Soccer |work=Major League Soccer |accessdate=January 15, 2019}}</ref> The Sounders finished second in the Western Conference with 18 wins, 11 losses, and 5 draws. With 14 wins in the final 16 matches of the season, the Sounders completed the best half season in league history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=October 28, 2018 |title=Decision Day drama rockets Sounders into MLS playoff bye, win over San Jose |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/decision-day-drama-rockets-sounders-into-mls-playoff-bye-win-over-san-jose/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> Minority owner Paul Allen died from complications related to [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]] on October 15, 2018, leaving his stake in the Sounders to an estate executed by his sister [[Jody Allen]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Booth |first=Tim |date=October 16, 2018 |title=Future of Paul Allen's sports holdings remains unclear |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2018/oct/16/future-of-paul-allens-sports-holdings-remains-uncl/ |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> Seattle then faced the Portland Timbers in the Conference Semifinals, losing the away leg 2\u20131 and winning the home leg 3\u20132 to tie the series on aggregate after extra time. In the ensuing penalty shootout, Portland won 4\u20132; the home leg is considered to be one of the best playoff matches in league history due to its dramatic finish.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=November 8, 2018 |title=Cascadia classic: Sounders' season ends on penalty kicks in wild loss to Timbers |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/one-for-the-ages-sounders-season-ends-on-penalty-kicks-in-wild-loss-to-timbers/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Creditor |first=Avi |date=November 9, 2018 |title=Timbers Outlast Rival Sounders in PKs to Advance After MLS Playoff Classic |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/11/09/seattle-sounders-portland-timbers-mls-playoffs-second-leg-pks-asprilla-ruidiaz |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2019: Second MLS Cup title====\n{{see also|2019 Seattle Sounders FC season|MLS Cup 2019}}\nThe 2019 MLS season began with the loss of team captain and inaugural season player [[Osvaldo Alonso]], who was released into free agency and signed with [[Minnesota United FC]] before the season began.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=January 10, 2019 |title=Sounders captain and original 2009 member Osvaldo Alonso signs with Minnesota United FC |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-captain-and-original-2009-member-osvaldo-alonso-signs-with-minnesota-united-fc/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref> Defender [[Chad Marshall]], who had joined in 2014, announced his retirement from professional soccer on May 22, leaving unexpectedly mid-way through the season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Evans |first=Jayda |date=May 22, 2019 |title=Sounders defender Chad Marshall announces retirement, ending 16-year MLS career |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-defender-chad-marshall-announces-retirement-ending-16-year-mls-career/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref> Despite the loss of these two players, plus the suspension of [[Rom\u00e1n Torres]] for ten matches for testing positive for a [[performance-enhancing substance]] in August,<ref>{{cite news |last=Evans |first=Jayda |date=August 2, 2019 |title=Sounders defender Roman Torres suspended 10 games for violating MLS substance-abuse policy |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-defender-roman-torres-suspended-10-games-for-violating-mls-substance-abuse-policy/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> the Sounders finished 2nd in the Western Conference and 4th in the overall league table, good enough to qualify for a spot in the 2020 CONCACAF Champions' League<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/08/27/how-mls-teams-could-qualify-2020-concacaf-champions-league | title=How MLS teams can qualify for the 2020 Concacaf Champions League | date=October 25, 2019 | accessdate=October 25, 2019 | first=Ian | last=Quillen}}</ref> and a record 11th-straight appearance in the MLS Cup Playoffs.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/10/07/mls-cup-playoff-power-rankings-postseason | title=MLS Playoff Power Rankings: Separating MLS Cup Contenders From the Pack | date=7 October 2019 | accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the playoffs, the Sounders were able to defeat the Supporters' Shield winning-team [[Los Angeles FC]] in the Conference Finals, leading them to face Toronto FC in the MLS Cup Final for the third time in 4 years. The Sounders won the game 3\u20131<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/11/10/seattle-sounders-fc-3-toronto-fc-1-2019-mls-cup-match-recap |title=Seattle Sounders FC 3, Toronto FC 1 {{!}} 2019 MLS Cup Match Recap | date=10 November 2019 | accessdate=11 November 2019 | first=Nick | last=Rosano}}</ref> in front of a franchise-record 69,274 fans at CenturyLink Field.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/11/10/2019-mls-cup-breaks-seattle-sounders-all-time-attendance-record | title=2019 MLS Cup breaks Seattle Sounders all-time attendance record | first=Tom | last=Bogert | date=10 November 2019 | accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Sounders uniform evolution ==\nKits used by various Sounders' franchises over the years:\n\n'''NASL Era (1974\u20131983)'''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Morrison |first1=Dave |title=NASL Jerseys Sounders |url=https://www.nasljerseys.com/Jerseys/Sounders_Jerseys_NASL.htm |website=North American Soccer League Jerseys |publisher=North American Soccer League Jerseys |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n{|\n|\n|{{Football kit\n| leftarm = 046A3C | body = FFFFFF | rightarm = 046A3C | shorts = 046ECC | socks = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la = _borderonwhite | pattern_ra = _borderonwhite | title = NASL Home<br>1974\u201377}}\n|\n|{{Football kit\n| leftarm = 046ECC | body = 046ECC | rightarm = 046ECC | shorts = FFFFFF | socks = FFFFFF\n| pattern_b = _sides_and_collar_on_white | pattern_la = _borderonwhite | pattern_ra = _borderonwhite | title = NASL Home<br>1978\u201379}}\n|{{Football kit\n| leftarm = 046ECC | body = 046ECC | rightarm = 046ECC | shorts = FFFFFF | socks = FFFFFF\n| pattern_b = _collarwithbodywhite | pattern_la = _borderonwhite | pattern_ra = _borderonwhite | title = NASL Home<br>1980\u201382}}\n|\n|{{Football kit\n| leftarm = 021f3e | body = 021f3e | rightarm = 021f3e | shorts = 021f3e | socks = 021f3e\n| pattern_b = _pinstripes_and_collar_on_white | pattern_la = _pinstripes_and_border_on_white | pattern_ra = _pinstripes_and_border_on_white | | pattern_sh = _adidaswhite | pattern_so = _color_3_stripes_on_white\n| title = NASL Home<br>1983}}\n|\n|{{Football kit\n| leftarm = 046A3C | body = 046A3C | rightarm = 046A3C | shorts = 046ECC | socks = 046A3C |\n| pattern_la = _whiteborder | pattern_ra = _whiteborder | title = NASL Away<br>1974\u201376}}\n|\n|{{Football kit\n| leftarm = 046A3C | body = 046A3C | rightarm = 046A3C | shorts = FFFFFF | socks = 046A3C\n| pattern_b = _sides_and_collar_white | pattern_la = _whiteborder | pattern_ra = _whiteborder | title = NASL Away<