|| 2001 || (13\u201312\u20131)\n|-\n| [[Brian Schmetzer]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2002\u20132008 || (103\u201350\u201345)\n|-\n| [[Sigi Schmid]] || {{flagicon|GER}} || 2009\u20132016 || (115\u201379\u201356)\n|-\n| [[Brian Schmetzer]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2016\u2013 || (59\u201336\u201326)\n|}\n\n=== Players ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Nat.\n! Years\n|-\n| [[John Rowland (Welsh footballer)|John Rowlands]] || {{flagicon|WAL}} || 1974\u20131976\n|-\n| [[Micky Cave]] || {{flagicon|ENG}} || 1977\u20131980\n|-\n| [[Bob Donaldson (soccer)|Bob Donaldson]] || {{flagicon|SCO}} || 1979\u20131983\n|-\n| [[Kevin Bond (English footballer)|Kevin Bond]] || {{flagicon|ENG}} || 1981\n|-\n| [[Peter Hattrup]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 1984\u20131989, 1994\u20131995, 1997\u20131999, 2001\n|-\n| [[Marcus Hahnemann]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 1994\u20131996, 2012\u20132014\n|-\n| [[Brian Ching]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2001\u20132002\n|-\n| [[Leighton O'Brien]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2001\u20132008\n|-\n| [[Zach Scott]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2002\u2013\n|-\n| [[Roger Levesque]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2003\u20132012\n|-\n| [[W\u00e9lton Ara\u00fajo Melo|W\u00e9lton]] || {{flagicon|BRA}} || 2004\u20132005\n|-\n| [[Taylor Graham]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2005, 2007\u20132011\n|-\n| [[S\u00e9bastien Le Toux]] \u00a4 || {{flagicon|FRA}} || 2007\u20132009\n|-\n| [[Kasey Keller]] || {{flagicon|USA}} || 2009\u20132011\n|-\n| [[Fredy Montero]] || {{flagicon|COL}} || 2009\u20132012\n|-\n| [[Steve Zakuani]] || {{flagicon|COD}} || 2009\u20132013\n|-\n| [[Freddie Ljungberg]] || {{flagicon|SWE}} || 2009\u20132010\n|-\n| [[Blaise Nkufo]] || {{flagicon|SUI}} || 2010\u20132011\n|}\n\n\u00a4 Played for two distinct Sounders franchises\n\n== Honors ==\n=== International ===\n'''[[CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions Cup]]'''\n* '''4th place (1):''' [[1996 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1996]]\n\n=== Domestic ===\n'''[[U.S. Open Cup]]'''\n* '''Winners (4):''' [[2009 U.S. Open Cup Final|2009]], [[2010 U.S. Open Cup Final|2010]], [[2011 U.S. Open Cup Final|2011]], [[2014 U.S. Open Cup Final|2014]]\n* '''Runners-up (1):''' [[2012 U.S. Open Cup Final|2012]]\n\n=== League ===\n==== MLS ====\n'''[[MLS Cup Playoffs]]'''\n* '''Conference Semifinalists (6):''' [[2009 MLS Cup Playoffs#Western Conference|2009]], [[2010 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2010]], [[2011 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference semifinals|2011]], [[2013 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2013]], [[2015 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2015]], [[2018 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2018]]\n* '''Conference Finalists (2):''' [[2012 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Championships|2012]], [[2014 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Championships|2014]]\n*'''Conference Champions (3):''' [[2016 MLS Cup Playoffs#MLS Cup|2016]], [[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#MLS Cup|2017]], [[2019 MLS Cup Playoffs#MLS Cup|2019]]\n* '''Winners (2):''' [[MLS Cup 2016|2016]], [[MLS Cup 2019|2019]]\n'''[[Supporters' Shield]]'''\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[2014 Major League Soccer season|2014]]\n\n==== NASL ====\n'''[[Soccer Bowl]]'''\n* '''Runner Up (2):''' [[1977 North American Soccer League season|1977]], [[1982 North American Soccer League season|1982]]\n\n'''[[Trans-Atlantic Challenge Cup]]'''\n\n* Winner 1981\n\n==== USL ====\n'''[[USL First Division|USL First Division Playoffs]]'''\n* '''Winners (4):''' 1995, 1996, 2005, 2007\n* '''Runners-up (1):''' 2004\n\n'''[[USL First Division|USL Commissioner's Cup]]''' (Best USL Regular Season Record)\n* '''Winners (3):''' 1994, 2002, 2007\n* '''Runners-up (1):''' 1995\n\n=== Other ===\n'''[[Cascadia Cup]]'''\n* '''Winners (6):''' 2006, 2007, 2011, 2015, 2018, 2019\n\n'''[[Heritage Cup (MLS)|Heritage Cup]]'''\n* '''Winners (7):''' 2010, 2011, 2013, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n\n== OL Reign, 2013\u2013present==\n{{main|OL Reign}}\nIn November 2012, it was confirmed that a Seattle-based women's professional soccer team owned by Bill Predmore (founder and CEO of Seattle-based digital marketing agency, POP) had been accepted into a new women's professional soccer league, later named the [[National Women's Soccer League]].<ref name=seattletimes_pr_112112>{{cite news|title=Seattle Club Selected as Founding Member of New Women's Professional Soccer League|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/soundersfcblog/2019731392_seattle_will_have_team_in_new.html|newspaper=Seattle Times|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=seattletimes_11212>{{cite news|title=A stop and chat with Bill Predmore, owner of the new women's pro team in Seattle|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/soundersfcblog/2019731718_a_stop_and_chat_with_bill_pred.html|newspaper=Seattle Times|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> Former general manager of the [[Seattle Sounders Women]] and [[Seattle Sounders FC]] Director of Youth Programs,<ref>{{cite web|title=Amy Carnell, the Sounders FC Director of Youth Programs since 2008, has helped build the largest youth camp system in Major League Soccer.|url=http://www.soundersfc.com/news/articles/2011/12-december/amy-carnell-sounders-women.aspx|publisher=Seattle Sounders FC|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> Amy Carnell, was named General Manager and [[Laura Harvey]] head coach. About a week before the season began, Carnell resigned and Harvey took on many of her responsibilities similar to her role with [[Arsenal Ladies]].\n\nOriginally known as Seattle Reign FC, they played their first season at [[Starfire Sports|Starfire Stadium]] in [[Tukwila, Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bird|first=Liviu|title=Seattle Reign FC announces Starfire Stadium as home venue|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2013/01/23/seattle-reign-fc-announces-starfire-stadium-as-home-venue/|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> The stadium is located approximately 12 miles from downtown [[Seattle]] and is the training facility for [[Seattle Sounders FC]], as well as where the Sounders play their [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] matches.\n\nFor the 2014 season, they moved to [[Memorial Stadium (Seattle)|Memorial Stadium]] on the [[Seattle Center]] grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/soundersfc/2014/02/06/reign-fc-confirms-its-new-home-will-be-seattle-memorial-stadium/ |title=Reign FC confirms its new home will be Seattle Memorial Stadium |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |work=Sounders FC Blog |publisher=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=February 6, 2014 |accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe club's lease on Memorial Stadium ended after the 2018 season, and the club faced a stadium crisis as that date approached. The stadium, owned by the [[Seattle School District]], dates to the 1940s and does not meet facility standards that were to be enforced by the NWSL and the [[United States Soccer Federation]] in 2019. Additionally, the district had announced plans to build a new high school in the area, with the stadium as the most likely site.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/features/will-reign-fc-thrive-or-just-survive-nwsls-cloudy-future-seattle |title=Will Reign FC thrive, or just survive? The NWSL's cloudy future in Seattle |first=Richard |last=Farley |magazine=[[FourFourTwo]] |date=September 27, 2017 |accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> Eventually, Predmore announced in January 2019 that the club would relocate to Tacoma and rebrand as Reign FC. As part of the move, separate minority stakes in the club were purchased by the ownership group of [[Minor League Baseball]]'s [[Tacoma Rainiers]], as well as Sounders FC principal owner [[Adrian Hanauer]] and his mother. Reign now play at [[Cheney Stadium]], home to both the Rainiers and the Sounders' reserve side, [[Tacoma Defiance]]. The Rainiers were already planning to build a new soccer-specific facility for the Defiance next to Cheney Stadium; upon its completion (expected for 2021), both the Defiance and Reign will move there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sounderatheart.com/2019/1/30/18203707/reign-owners-open-letter |title=An Open Letter to Fans and Supporters of Seattle Reign FC from the owners |first=Bill and Teresa |last=Predmore |work=Sounder at Heart |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |date=January 30, 2019 |accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, OL Groupe, the parent company of top-level French club [[Olympique Lyonnais]], purchased a majority stake in Reign FC in a transaction that closed in January 2020. OL Groupe purchased an 89.5% stake in the side; the Predmores retained 7.5%, and former NBA star [[Tony Parker]], a business partner of OL, purchased 3%.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levine |first1=Matthew |title=OL Groupe to become majority owner of National Women\u2019s Soccer League\u2019s Reign FC |url=http://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/ol-groupe-to-become-majority-owner-of-national-womens-soccer-leagues-reign-fc |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |publisher=NWSL}}</ref> The new owners announced the rebranding of the team as [[OL Reign]] on March 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Reign FC Reveal New Name and Brand Identity |url=https://www.olreign.com/news/2020/3/6/reign-fc-reveal-new-name-and-brand-identity |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |publisher=OL Reign |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reign Season-by-Season Results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!League\n!Regular Season\n!Playoffs\n!Avg. Attendance\n|-\n|[[2013 Seattle Reign FC season|2013]]\n|[[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n|7th Place\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2,306\n|-\n|[[2014 Seattle Reign FC season|2014]]\n|[[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n|1st Place\n|Runner-up\n|3,632\n|-\n| [[2015 Seattle Reign FC season|2015]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 1st Place\n| Runner-up\n| 4,060\n|-\n| [[2016 Seattle Reign FC season|2016]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 5th Place\n| ''Did not qualify''\n| 4,602\n|-\n| [[2017 Seattle Reign FC season|2017]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 5th Place\n| ''Did not qualify''\n| 4,037\n|-\n| [[2018 Seattle Reign FC season|2018]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 3rd Place\n| Semifinals\n| 3,824\n|-\n| [[2019 Reign FC season|2019]]\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| 4th Place\n| Semifinals\n| 5,213\n|}\n\n==Seattle Impact==\n{{main|Seattle Impact}}\n\nIn 2014, the [[Major Arena Soccer League]] awarded an expansion to former Tacoma Star player Dion Earl. The '''Seattle Impact''' played its inaugural season at the [[ShoWare Center]]. However, in January 2015, the team was sold to the semi-professional [[Tacoma Stars (2003)|Tacoma Stars]], who completed the season under the Stars' name.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Women's association football}}\n* [[Gorilla FC]]\n* [[OL Reign]]\n* [[Seattle Sounders (1974\u201383)]]\n* [[Seattle Sounders FC results by opponent]]\n* [[Seattle Sounders \u2013 Portland Timbers rivalry|Sounders\u2013Timbers rivalry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n* [http://soundersfc.com Sounders FC website]\n* [https://olreign.com OL Reign website]\n\n{{Seattle Sounders FC}}\n{{OL Reign}}\n{{USSoccer}}\n\n{{Seattle Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of professional soccer in Seattle}}\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders (1994\u20132008)]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders FC]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders (1974\u20131983)]]\n[[Category:OL Reign]]\n[[Category:History of soccer in the United States|Seattle]]\n[[Category:History of Seattle]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_soccer_in_Seattle"}
{"title_page": "American Crime (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 American crime drama television series}}\n{{About-distinguish|the ABC TV series|American Crime Story}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = American Crime\n| image                    = American Crime (TV series).jpg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Crime drama]]\n| creator                  = [[John Ridley]]\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Felicity Huffman]]\n* [[Timothy Hutton]]\n* [[W. Earl Brown]]\n* [[Richard Cabral]]\n* [[Caitlin Gerard]]\n* [[Benito Martinez (actor)|Benito Martinez]]\n* [[Penelope Ann Miller]]\n* [[Elvis Nolasco]]\n* Johnny Ortiz\n* [[Lili Taylor]]\n* [[Trevor Jackson (performer)|Trevor Jackson]]\n* [[Connor Jessup]]\n* [[Joey Pollari]]\n* Angelique Rivera\n* [[Regina King]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| composer                 = [[Mark Isham]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Spanish\n*French}}\n| num_seasons              = 3\n| num_episodes             = 29\n| list_episodes            = List of American Crime episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*John Ridley\n*Michael J. McDonald\n*[[Julie H\u00e9bert]]}}\n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = \n| location                 = [[Austin, Texas]]<br />[[Los Angeles]], California\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 43 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* The International Famous Players Radio Pictures Corporation Entertainment Company\n* Stearns Castle Entertainment\n* [[ABC Studios]]}}\n| distributor              = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist|\n*[[720p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n*[[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])}}\n| network                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| audio_format             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Stereo]]\n*[[Dolby Digital]] 5.1\n}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|3|5}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2017|4|30}}\n| related                  = \n| website_title            = Official website\n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''American Crime''''' is an American [[Anthology series|anthology]] [[crime drama]] television series that aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from March 5, 2015, to April 30, 2017.<ref name=\"TVBTN\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/11/19/abc-announces-premiere-dates-for-american-crime-and-secrets-and-lies/329680/|title=ABC Announces Premiere Dates for 'American Crime' and 'Secrets and Lies'|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=November 19, 2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> The series was created by [[John Ridley]], and starred [[Felicity Huffman]], [[Timothy Hutton]] and [[Regina King]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Alessandra |last=Stanley |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/05/arts/television/review-american-crime-a-series-where-justice-is-far-from-black-or-white.html |title=Review: 'American Crime,' a Series Where Justice Is Far From Black or White |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 4, 2015 |accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> The first season centered on race, class, and gender politics as it followed the lives of the participants in a trial who are forever changed during the legal process.<ref name=\"andreeva508\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/05/abc-picks-up-shonda-rhimes-how-to-get-away-with-murder-anthony-anderson-american-crime/|title=ABC New Series Pickups: 'Selfie', 'Forever', Galavant', 'Whispers', 'How To Get Away With Murder', 'American Crime', 'Black-ish', Jeff Lowell Comedy|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"variety508\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/abc-orders-viola-davis-drama-how-to-get-away-with-murder-1201176035/|title=ABC Orders 'Marvel's Agent Carter,' 4 Other Dramas and 4 Comedies|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe series was renewed for a second season in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/american-crime-castle-agents-of-shield-agent-carter-galavant-secrets-lies-fresh-off-the-boat-renewed-abc-1201422717/ |title='American Crime', 'Castle' 'S.H.I.E.L.D.', 'Agent Carter', 'Galavant', 'Secrets & Lies', 'Nashville' Among ABC Renewals |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=May 7, 2015 |accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> The second season, which premiered on-demand on December 17, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|last=Krolak|first=Mike|title=Watch American Crime Season 2 Premiere Online Free: Early Release|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/american-crime/news/updates/watch-american-crime-season-2-premiere-online-free-151217|publisher=ABC|accessdate=December 21, 2015|date=December 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=USA's 'Colony,' Fox's 'Second Chance' Receive Early Premieres Online|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/usa-colony-premiere-online-second-chance-american-crime-1201666345/|accessdate=December 22, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 21, 2015}}</ref> and premiered on ABC on January 6, 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/american-crime-season-2-premiere-date-time-slot-abc-1201611658/|title='American Crime' Gets January Return Date, New Time Slot on ABC|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> featured a new storyline and characters, with some actors from the first season\u2014including Huffman, Hutton, [[Regina King]], [[Elvis Nolasco]], [[Richard Cabral]], and [[Lili Taylor]]\u2014playing different characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewrap.com/american-crime-will-feature-same-actors-in-different-roles-in-season-2/ |title='American Crime' Will Feature Same Actors in Different Roles in Season 2 |publisher=The Wrap |first=Linda |last=Ge |date=May 12, 2015 |accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor\"/> In May 2016, ABC renewed the series for a third season,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/05/12/american-crime-renewed-abc-season-3/ |title=American Crime Renewed at ABC |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref> which starred Huffman, Hutton and King.<ref name=\"s3huffman\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/american-crime-felicity-huffman-return-season-3-1201781289/ |title='American Crime': Felicity Huffman Set To Return For Season 3 |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=June 29, 2016 |accessdate=June 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"s3details\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/american-crime-regina-king-return-details-season-3-abc-1201776113/ |title='American Crime': Regina King Set To Return, Details About Season 3 Revealed |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=June 20, 2016 |accessdate=June 21, 2016}}</ref> The third season premiered on March 12, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/abc-midseason-schedule-time-after-time-american-crime-the-catch-dirty-dancing-others-get-premiere-dates-1201882316/|title=ABC Midseason Schedule: 'Time After Time', 'American Crime', 'The Catch', 'Dirty Dancing', Others Get Premiere Dates|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 10, 2017|date=January 10, 2017}}</ref> On May 11, 2017, ABC cancelled the series after three seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/american-crime-canceled-abc-3-seasons-1202090548/|title='American Crime' Canceled By ABC After 3 Seasons|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=May 11, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAll three seasons of ''American Crime'' received critical acclaim. In 2015, the series received ten [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, including for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Miniseries|Outstanding Limited Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special|Writing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special]] (Ridley), [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Lead Actress in a Miniseries or Movie]] (Huffman), [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie|Lead Actor in a Miniseries or Movie]] (Hutton), [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie|Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Movie]] (Cabral), and a win for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Movie]] (King). In 2016, it received four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, including another for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Miniseries|Outstanding Limited Series]], with Huffman and Taylor being both nominated for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Lead Actress in a Miniseries or Movie]] and King receiving a second win for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Movie]].\n\n== Overview ==\nThe first season takes place in [[Modesto, California]], where a war veteran becomes the victim of a home invasion gone wrong and the lives of four people are forever changed after each one is connected to the crime.\n\nThe second season takes place in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], where the co-captains of a private school's basketball team are accused of sexually assaulting a male classmate and posting photographs of the incident online.\n\nThe third season takes place in [[Alamance County, North Carolina]], where five people struggle to survive in a place where the American Dream comes with a price.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n===Season 1===\n====Main====\n* [[Felicity Huffman]] as Barbara \"Barb\" Hanlon\n* [[Timothy Hutton]] as Russ Skokie\n* [[W. Earl Brown]] as Thomas \"Tom\" Carlin\n* [[Richard Cabral]] as Hector Tontz\n* [[Caitlin Gerard]] as Aubry Taylor\n* [[Benito Martinez (actor)|Benito Martinez]] as Alonzo Guti\u00e9rrez\n* [[Penelope Ann Miller]] as Eve Carlin\n* [[Elvis Nolasco]] as Carter Nix\n* Johnny Ortiz as Anthony \"Tony\" Guti\u00e9rrez\n\n====Recurring====\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Regina King]] as Aliyah Shadeed<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/regina-king-joins-american-crime-720399|title=Regina King Joins 'American Crime,' Will Direct 'Scandal,' Return to 'Big Bang Theory'|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 22, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref> (born Doreen Nix), Carter Nix's sister and a [[Religious conversion|convert to]] [[Islam]]\n* [[David Hoflin]] as Mark Skokie, Barb and Russ' younger son, on leave from the Army\n* [[Gwendoline Yeo]] as Richelle, Mark's fianc\u00e9e\n* Gleendylis Inoa as Jennifer \"Jenny\" Guti\u00e9rrez, the sister of Tony and daughter of Alonzo Guti\u00e9rrez\n* [[Lili Taylor]] as Nancy Straumberg<ref>{{cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/12/18/lili-taylor-american-crime/|title=First look at Lili Taylor on ABC's 'American Crime'|work=Entertainment Weekly|first=Kevin P.|last=Sullivan|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n* Kira Pozehl as Gwendolyn \"Gwen\" Skokie, Matt's wife who is in a coma after being beaten during a home invasion\n* Grant Merritt as Matt Skokie, Gwen's husband who was killed during a home invasion\n* Bob Hess as Michael Taylor, Aubry's father\n* [[Jennifer Savidge]] as Ruth Taylor, Aubry's mother\n* Joe Nemmers as Deputy D.A. Rick Soderbergh\n* Brent Anderson as Detective Chuck Palmer\n* Todd Terry as Jackson, defense attorney for Hector Tontz\n}}\n\n===Season 2===\n====Main====\n* [[Felicity Huffman]] as Leslie Graham, the private school's manipulative principal<ref name=\"Season2\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/american-crime-season-2-john-ridley-1201554723/|title=John Ridley Reveals Season Two Plot of 'American Crime' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|work=Variety|date=August 1, 2015|accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Huffman and Hutton\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/felicity-huffman-timothy-hutton-return-american-crime-season-2-abc-1201427118/ |title=Felicity Huffman & Timothy Hutton To Return To 'American Crime' For Season 2 |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=May 14, 2015 |accessdate=May 14, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Timothy Hutton]] as Dan Sullivan, the school's basketball coach<ref name=\"Season2\" /><ref name=\"Huffman and Hutton\"/>\n* [[Lili Taylor]] as Anne Blaine, Taylor's mother<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/lili-taylor-cast-american-crime-season-2-regular-1201453590/ |title=Lili Taylor Returning To 'American Crime' Season 2 As Regular |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=June 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Season2\" />\n* [[Elvis Nolasco]] as Chris Dixon, a public school's principal<ref name=\"Season2\" /><ref name=nc>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/american-crime-richard-cabral-elvis-nolasco-abc-1201451883/|title=American Crime Season 2: Richard Cabral, Elvis Nolasco Set To Return|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Trevor Jackson (performer)|Trevor Jackson]] as Kevin LaCroix, a private school student and captain of the basketball team<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/08/trevor-jackson-american-crime-jenna-dewan-tatum-supergirl-1201491174/ |title=Trevor Jackson Joins 'American Crime'; Jenna Dewan-Tatum Cast In 'Supergirl' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=August 3, 2015 |accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Connor Jessup]] as Taylor Blaine, the sexual assault accuser<ref name=\"Season2\" /><ref name=cjar>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/american-crime-adds-connor-jessup-angelique-rivera-1201483359/|title=Connor Jessup, Angelique Rivera Join 'American Crime' Season 2 Lineup|first=Ross A.|last=Lincoln|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Joey Pollari]] as Eric Tanner, the [[closeted]] gay basketball player accused of sexual assault by Taylor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/abcs-american-crime-adds-joey-pollari-as-season-regular-1201482976/|title=Joey Pollari Joins 'American Crime' As Season 2 Regular|first=Ross A.|last=Lincoln|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n* Angelique Rivera as Evy Dominguez, Taylor's girlfriend and a witness to the crime<ref name=cjar/>\n* [[Regina King]] as Terri LaCroix, Kevin's strict mother<ref name=\"Season2\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/regina-king-return-american-crime-season-2-series-regular-1201445187/ |title=Regina King To Return To 'American Crime' As Series Regular In Season 2 |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=June 16, 2015 |accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Recurring====\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Hope Davis]] as Steph Sullivan, Coach Sullivan's wife<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/american-crime-adds-hope-davis-to-season-2-cast-exclusive/|title='American Crime' Adds Hope Davis to Season 2 Cast (Exclusive)|website=TheWrap|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Faran Tahir]] as Rhys Bashir, the chairman of the board at Leyland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/faran-tahir-cast-american-crime-holly-curran-amazon-pilot-zelda-1201484861/ |title=Faran Tahir Cast In ABC's 'American Crime'|first=Denise|last=Petski|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00e9 3000|Andr\u00e9 L. Benjamin]] as Michael LaCroix, Kevin's father<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/andre-benjamin-cast-american-crime-john-ridley-regina-king-1201489026/|title=Andr\u00e9 Benjamin Joins ABC Drama Series 'American Crime'|first=Denise|last=Petski|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 31, 2015|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Emily Bergl]] as Lillah Tanner, Eric's mother who seems to have a hard time accepting her son's homosexuality after he is outed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Emily Bergl Joins ABC's 'American Crime'; Travis Mills In 'Flaked'|url=http://deadline.com/2015/08/emily-bergl-cast-abc-american-crime-travis-mills-flaked-1201507008/|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Stanley]] as Charles, a businessman and Dr. Graham's boyfriend<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandberg|first=Bryn Elise|title=Christopher Stanley Joins 'American Crime' Season Two (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/christopher-stanley-joins-american-crime-821834|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 10, 2015|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref>\n*Brent Anderson as Curt Tanner, Eric's father. Unlike his wife he tries to make an effort to come to terms with Eric being gay. \n* [[Stephanie Sigman]] as Monica Salazar, an administrator at a public school and colleague of Dixon<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Stephanie Sigman Joins 'American Crime'; Michael Maize In 'Hawaii Five-O'|url=http://deadline.com/2015/08/stephanie-sigman-cast-american-crime-john-ridley-1201501762/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Richard Cabral]] as Sebastian De La Torre, a [[White hat (computer security)|white hat]] computer [[Hacker (computer security)|hacker]]<ref name=nc/>\n* Lynn Blackburn as Cammy Ross, a reporter for a local media outlet\n* Sky Azure Van Vliet as Becca Sullivan, Coach Sullivan's daughter and a cheerleader\n* Michael Seitz as Wes Baxter, a basketball player at Leyland\n* Ty Doran as Peter Tanner, Eric's brother and a student at Marshall\n}}\n\n===Season 3===\n====Main====\n* [[Felicity Huffman]] as Jeanette Hesby<ref name=\"s3huffman\"/><ref name=\"Roberts\"/>\n* [[Timothy Hutton]] as Nicholas Coates<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/07/american-crime-timothy-hutton-return-season-3-john-ridley-abc-1201792313/|title='American Crime': Timothy Hutton Set To Return For Season 3|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=July 25, 2016|accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Bizet\">{{Cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/american-crime-mickaelle-bizet-mary-louise-parker-guest-star-billions-1201856014/|title='American Crime' Adds Micka\u00eblle X. Bizet; Mary Louise Parker To Guest In 'Billions'|first=Denise|last=Petski|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=November 17, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lili Taylor]] as Clair Coates, Nicholas' wife<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/01/american-crime-lili-taylor-cast-season-3/|title=American Crime's Lili Taylor Re-Ups for Transformational Season 3 Role|website=TVLine|last=Roots|first=Kimberly|date=August 1, 2016|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Bizet\"/>\n* [[Connor Jessup]] as Coy Henson, a young American who is addicted to drugs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/17/american-crime-season-3-connor-jessup-cast/|title=American Crime: Connor Jessup Sets 'Shocking' Season 3 Return|website=TVLine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=August 17, 2016|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TV Series Finale\"/>\n* [[Richard Cabral]] as Isaac Castillo, a farm crew chief<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/07/american-crime-richard-cabral-return-season-3-1201784262/|title='American Crime': Richard Cabral Set To Return For Season 3|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=July 8, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TV Series Finale\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/american-crime-season-three-synopsis-released-whos-coming-back/|title=''American Crime:'' Season Three Synopsis Released; Who's Coming Back?|first=Jessica|last=Pena|website=TV Series Finale|date=January 3, 2017|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Benito Martinez (actor)|Benito Martinez]] as Luis Salazar, a father from Mexico who wants to find his missing son<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/american-crime-benito-martinez-cast-season-3-abc-1201806909/|title='American Crime': Benito Martinez To Return For Season 3 Of ABC Series|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=August 22, 2016|accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TV Series Finale\"/>\n* [[Regina King]] as Kimara Walters, a social worker who wants to have a baby<ref name=\"s3details\"/>\n\n====Recurring====\n* [[Sandra Oh]] as Abby Tanaka<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/sandra-oh-american-crime-season-3-arrowverse-crossover-dominators-1201873877/|title=TV News Roundup: Sandra Oh Joins 'American Crime' Season 3|work=Variety|last=Roshanian|first=Arya|date=September 29, 2016|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Cherry Jones]] as Laurie Ann Hesby, the matriarch of Hesby Farms<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/cherry-jones-american-crime-season-3-1201864000/|title=Cherry Jones Joins Cast of 'American Crime' Season 3 (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|date=September 20, 2016|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TV Series Finale\"/>\n* [[Tim DeKay]] as JD Hesby, Laurie Ann's brother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/10/tim-dekay-cast-american-crime-season-3-abc-1201844161/|title='American Crime': Tim DeKay Joins Cast For Season 3 Of ABC Series|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 27, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Janel Moloney]] as Raelyn, Jeanette's sister, a single mother recently abandoned by her husband.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/american-crime-season-3-janel-moloney-abc-1201891137/|title='The West Wing' Alum Janel Moloney Joins ABC's 'American Crime' Season 3 (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Dallas Roberts]] as Carson Hesby, Jeanette's husband<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{Cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/american-crime-dallas-roberts-cast-season-3-abc-series-1201850279/|title='American Crime': Dallas Roberts Joins Cast For Season 3 Of ABC Series|first=Denise|last=Petski|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Ana Mulvoy-Ten]] as Shae Reese, a 17-year-old sex worker<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/ana-mulvoy-ten-american-crime-season-3-cast-abc-1201900015/|title='American Crime' Adds Former Nickelodeon Star to Season 3 as Series Regular (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|work=Variety|date=October 25, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TV Series Finale\"/>\n* Micka\u00eblle X. Bizet as Gabrielle Durand, a Haitian woman, the nanny of the Coates' son<ref name=\"Bizet\"/><ref name=\"TV Series Finale\"/>\n* Clayton Cardenas as Diego Castillo<ref name=\"TV Series Finale\"/>\n\n==Production==\n===Development and casting===\nIn October 2013, ABC announced it was developing a drama [[television pilot|pilot]] created by [[John Ridley]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/abc-john-ridley-12-years-a-slave-murder-drama-american-crime/ |title=ABC To Tackle Race With Murder Drama From '12 Years A Slave' Writer John Ridley |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=October 24, 2013 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> In January 2014, ABC greenlighted the pilot, and signed a deal with Ridley to direct.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/abc-gives-pilot-green-light-to-john-ridleys-racially-charged-murder-drama-american-crime|title=ABC Gives Pilot Green Light To John Ridley's Racially-Charged Murder Drama 'American Crime' &#124;Shadow and Act|last=Obenson|first=Tambay A.|website=Indiewire|date=January 15, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224043701/http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/abc-gives-pilot-green-light-to-john-ridleys-racially-charged-murder-drama-american-crime|archive-date=February 24, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/12-years-a-slave-oscar-672827 |title='12 Years a Slave' Oscar Nominee to Direct ABC Pilot (Exclusive) |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=January 21, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Elvis Nolasco]] and [[Caitlin Gerard]] were the first regular members to be cast, as announced on February 14, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/gerlald-mcraney-joins-tnt-pilot-agent-x-duo-cast-in-abcs-american-crime/ |title=Gerlald McRaney Joins TNT Pilot 'Agent X'; Duo Cast In ABC's 'American Crime' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> Later [[Richard Cabral]], Johnny Ortiz, [[Benito Martinez (actor)|Benito Martinez]] and [[W. Earl Brown]] were cast for regular supporting roles in the pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/american-crime-agent-x-and-warriors-pilots-add-cast/ |title='American Crime', 'Agent X' And 'Warriors' Pilots Add Cast |website=Deadline Hollywood |date= February 21, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/03/benito-martinez-w-earl-brown-john-ridley-abc-pilot-american-crime/ |title=Benito Martinez & W. Earl Brown To Co-Star In John Ridley's ABC Pilot 'American Crime' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> In early March, [[Timothy Hutton]] was cast in a lead role as Russ, and [[Penelope Ann Miller]] signed on in a supporting role of the mother of the murdered man's wife.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/timothy-hutton-star-john-ridleys-686422 |title=Timothy Hutton to Star in John Ridley's ABC Drama |work=Hollywood Reporter |date=March 5, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/03/penelope-ann-miller-joins-abcs-american-crime-chris-butler-in-nbcs-lifesaver/ |title=Penelope Ann Miller Joins ABC's 'American Crime', Chris Butler In NBC's 'Lifesaver' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 5, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> Soon thereafter, it was announced that [[Felicity Huffman]] was cast in the lead role of Barb Skokie, Russ' stoic ex-wife and mother of the murdered young man.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/03/felicity-huffman-american-crime-john-ridley-abc/ |title=Felicity Huffman To Star In John Ridley's ABC Pilot 'American Crime' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 7, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/felicity-huffman-star-abc-drama-686812 |title=Felicity Huffman to Star in ABC Drama From '12 Years a Slave' Writer |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 7, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe pilot episode, along with further episodes, was filmed in [[Austin, Texas]], which substitutes for the California city of [[Modesto, California|Modesto]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rowland |first=Marijke |url=http://www.modbee.com/2014/06/22/3404379/abc-crime-drama-will-be-set-in.html |title=ABC crime drama will be set in Modesto; local reaction mixed |work=The Modesto Bee |date=June 22, 2014 |accessdate=August 4, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808041124/http://www.modbee.com/2014/06/22/3404379/abc-crime-drama-will-be-set-in.html |archive-date=August 8, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On May 8, 2014, ABC picked up the pilot to the series for the 2014\u201315 television season.<ref name=andreeva508/><ref name=variety508/>\n\nFilming for the series moved to [[Los Angeles]], California with the third season, as the show's production was awarded a California tax credit.<ref name=\"s3details\"/>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of American Crime episodes}}\n{{:List of American Crime episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n''American Crime'' was met with wide acclaim from critics with many praising the writing, directing, and the acting abilities of its cast (particularly [[Felicity Huffman]] and [[Regina King]]). [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gave the first season a rating of 96% based on 45 reviews with an average rating of 8.32 out of 10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Raw, emotional portrayals of diverse characters in dire pain, mashed up with chilling narratives and a gutsy attitude make ''American Crime'' a must-see.\"<ref name=rtmt>{{cite  web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/american-crime/s01/|title=American Crime: Season 1|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=May 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the first season a score of 85 out of 100, based on 35 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/american-crime/season-1|title=American Crime: Season 1|website=Metacritic|accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' critic Dominic Patten said in his review: \"the 11-episode limited series marks a resounding flag planting by network television and tells cable that it doesn't own poignant drama on our small screens.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/03/american-crime-review-john-ridley-timothy-hutton-dominic-patten-1201385856/|title='American Crime' Review: John Ridley Drama With Timothy Hutton, Felicity Huffman|first=Dominic|last=Patten|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=March 4, 2015}}</ref> Critic Ed Bark praised the performance of Felicity Huffman and wrote that she would be a favorite to win at [[67th Primetime Emmy Awards|next year's Primetime Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unclebarky.com/reviews_files/b330d895511e21704d32783aa4c566c6-1921.html|title=ABC's American Crime soars on the strength of its daring, daunting premise|website=UncleBarky.com|first=Ed|last=Bark|date=March 4, 2014|accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe second season continued to receive critical acclaim from critics. On Rotten Tomatoes, the season has a 97% rating based on 37 reviews with an average score of 8.34 out of 10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''American Crime''{{'}}s intense second season infuses a complicated, topical story with genuine emotion, and patiently allows its narrative arc to develop without sacrificing momentum.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/american-crime/s02/|title=American Crime: Season 2|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, it has a score of 85 out of 100 based on 26 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/american-crime/season-2|title=American Crime: Season 2|website=Metacritic|accessdate=January 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received even higher acclaim than its first two seasons. On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 100% rating, based on 31 reviews with an average score of 9 out of 10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''American Crime'' offers a unique anthology series filled with surprising revelations and compelling inter-connected narratives that opt for original, emotional human commentary instead of tired arguments over current events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/american-crime/s03/|title=American Crime: Season 3|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref> On Metacritic, it has a score of 90 out of 100, based on 26 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/american-crime/season-3|title=American Crime: Season 3|website=Metacritic|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref> Verne Gay of ''[[Newsday]]'' calls it \"Another brilliant, powerful, moving season of one of TV's best.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/american-crime-review-season-3-just-as-brilliant-powerful-1.13229984 |title='American Crime' review: Season 3 just as brilliant, powerful |work=Newsday |first=Verne |last=Gay |date=March 8, 2017 |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:8%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! style=\"width:20%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Timeslot ([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|ET]])\n! style=\"width:5%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Episodes\n! colspan=\"2\"| Premiered\n! colspan=\"2\"| Ended\n! style=\"width:10%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| TV<br />season\n! style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Rank\n! style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 18&ndash;49<br/>average\n! style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Overall viewership (including DVR)\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date\n! span style=\"width:10%; font-size:smaller; line-height:100%;\"| <small>Viewers<br />(in millions)</small>\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date\n! span style=\"width:10%; font-size:smaller; line-height:100%;\"|  {{small|Viewers<br />(in millions)}}\n|-\n| [[List of American Crime episodes#Season 1 (2015)|1]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|<small>Thursday 10:00&nbsp;p.m.</small>\n| 11\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>March 5, 2015</center>\n| 8.37<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/03/06/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-american-idol-the-blacklist-adjusted-up/371969/|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big 